# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: crimean-war
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The Russian Empire formally annexed the Crimean Khanate on 19 April [O.S.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] 8 April] 1783, following a decade-long campaign of intervention in the Crimean Peninsula.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Russia aimed to control the Black Sea and end raids by Crimean slavers into its territory.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] To accomplish this, the Russians waged a series of wars against the Ottoman Empire and its Crimean vassal state, culminating in victory in the 1768–1774 Russo-Turkish War.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The Treaty of Küçük Kaynarca, signed in 1774, granted the Crimean Khanate nominal independence from the Ottomans under Russian influence.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] In subsequent years, Russia would intervene widely in Crimean affairs, provoking a series of revolts by the Crimean Tatars, while the Ottomans watched in ambivalence.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Crimea was finally annexed by Russia on 19 April 1783, after Russian imperial advisor Prince Grigory Potemkin encouraged Empress Catherine the Great to dissolve the khanate and formally claim its territory.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The annexation ended the centuries-long Crimean slave trade.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Under Russian administration, the former khanate was subjected to a long-term policy of de-Tatarisation.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Tatar property was confiscated, and Russians were encouraged to settle in the region, sparking waves of Tatar emigration.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Crimea came under control of the Mongol Golden Horde in the mid-13th century AD.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The Crimean Khanate was established in 1441 when Tatar Khan Hacı Giray broke away from the Horde.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The khanate became an Ottoman protectorate from 1475, with the southern shore of the Crimean Peninsula incorporated directly into the Ottoman Empire as a sanjak centred on the city of Kaffa (modern Feodosia).
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] This area was reorganised as Kaffa Eyalet in 1582.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The Crimeans conducted frequent raids into neighbouring territories of Poland, Lithuania and Muscovy, capturing inhabitants and selling them as slaves to the Ottoman Empire in what is known as the "Crimean slave trade".
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The Muscovite government paid regular tribute to the Khanate to ransom the captives.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Discontent with these raids eventually led to the Russo-Turkish War of 1735–1739, the first invasion of Crimea by the Russian Empire.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The Russians ultimately withdrew, and the resulting Treaty of Niš ended the conflict.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Upon Catherine the Great's accession to the Russian throne, diplomat Mikhail Illarionovich Vorontsov provided information about the khanate, suggesting to her that Russian rule of Crimea, or removal of the Ottomans from it, was the only way to vacate the danger it posed.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] During the Russo-Turkish War of 1768–1774, Russia invaded Crimea.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] In July 1771, the Russian army marched into Kaffa, and the Ottoman governor of Kaffa Eyalet was forced to flee to Constantinople.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Then leader of the Crimean Khanate, Selim Giray, surrendered to the invaders on 13 July.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Selim hoped that Russia would grant Crimea independence and maintain Giray rule.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Under pressure from the Russians, the Crimean elite elected Sahib Giray as their new khan.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] In November 1771, a group of Crimean envoys led by *Kalgay* Şahin Giray visited Saint Petersburg to discuss the creation of an independent Crimean state under Russian protection.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] In November 1772, representatives of Russia and Khan Sahib concluded the Treaty of Karasu Bazaar, which proclaimed the establishment of an independent state, including the former Kaffa Eyalet, and Russo-Crimean friendship.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] This could not come into effect without Ottoman recognition, however, which eventually came in 1774 with their defeat and the resulting Treaty of Küçük Kaynarca, wherein Russia and the Ottoman Empire agreed to Crimean independence.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Within two months of the signing of the treaty, however, the khanate government sent envoys to the Ottomans, requesting that they "destroy the conditions of independence".
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The envoys said that as Russian troops remained stationed in Crimea at Yeni-Kale and Kerch, the khanate could not be considered independent.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Nevertheless, the Ottomans ignored this request, not wishing to violate the agreement with Russia, which had granted it the right to garrison troops in these areas.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] In the disorder that followed the Turkish defeat, Tatar leader Devlet Giray refused to accept the treaty at the time of its signing.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Having been fighting Russians in the Kuban during the war, he crossed the Kerch Strait to Crimea and seized Kaffa.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Devlet subsequently seized the Crimean throne, usurping Khan Sahib.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Despite his actions against the Russians, Russian empress Catherine the Great recognised Devlet as Khan.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] At the same time, however, she was grooming her favourite Şahin Giray, now resident at her court, for the role.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] As time went on, the rule of Devlet became increasingly untenable.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] In July 1775, he sent a group of envoys to Constantinople to negotiate a re-entry of the Crimean Khanate into the Ottoman Empire.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] This action was in direct defiance of the Treaty of Küçük Kaynarca, which he asked the Ottomans to scrap.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Famed diplomat Ahmed Resmî Efendi, who had helped draft the treaty, refused to provide any assistance to the khanate, not wanting to start another disastrous war with Russia.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Catherine gave an order to invade Crimea in November 1776.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Her forces quickly gained control of Perekop, at the entrance to the peninsula.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] In January 1777, Russian-supported Şahin Giray crossed into Crimea over the Kerch Strait, much as Devlet had done.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Devlet, aware of his impending defeat, abdicated and fled to Constantinople. Şahin was installed as a puppet Khan, infuriating the Muslim population of the peninsula.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] When he heard this news, Ottoman Sultan Abdul Hamid I noted "Şahin Giray is a tool.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The aim of the Russians is to take Crimea." Şahin, a member of the ruling House of Giray, attempted a series of reforms to "modernise" the khanate.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] These included attempts to centralise power in the hands of the Khan, establishing "autocratic" rule, much as in Russia.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Previously, power had been distributed between the leaders of different clans, called *beys*.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] He attempted to institute state taxation, a conscripted and centralised army, and to replace the traditional religion-based Ottoman legal system with civil law.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] These reforms, aimed at disrupting the old Ottoman order, were despised by the Crimean populace.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] At the behest of Catherine, Şahin allowed Russians to settle in the peninsula, further infuriating Crimeans.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] A group of these settlers had been sent to Yeni-Kale, which remained under Russian control following the installation of Şahin as Khan.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Local residents banded together to prevent the Russian settlement, rebelling against Şahin.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] He sent the new conscript army he had created to quash the rebellion, only to see his forces defect to the rebels.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Revolt spread across the peninsula, and rebel forces advanced on Şahin's palace in Bakhchysarai.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Amidst this rebellion, exiled Crimeans in Constantinople pressed the Ottoman government to act.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Bowing to pressure, the government sent a fleet to Crimea, ostensibly to preserve the Treaty of Küçük Kaynarca.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Russian forces arrived at Yeni-Kale in February 1778, crushing the revolt before the Ottoman fleet arrived.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] When the fleet arrived in March, it found that there were no rebels left to support.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] It fought a brief skirmish with the Russian navy off Akitar (modern Sevastopol), but was "forced" to flee. Şahin was reinstated as Khan.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Minor skirmishes between the Ottoman and Russian navies continued until October 1778, when the Ottoman fleet returned defeated to Constantinople.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Over the following years, Şahin continued to try and reform the khanate.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Support for his reform programme remained low, and it was seriously undermined by the decision of Catherine to resettle the Crimean Pontic Greeks on the northern shores of the Azov Sea, outside the khanate.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] That community, which was Christian, was an essential part of the Crimean merchant class, and had most readily supported Şahin's reforms.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] This resettlement caused significant damage to the Crimean economy, and further weakened the position of the Khan.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Recognising defeat in Crimea, the Ottoman Empire signed the Convention of Aynali Kavak in early 1779.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] In the agreement, the Ottomans recognised Şahin as Khan of Crimea, promised no further intervention in Crimea, and conceded that Crimea was under Russian influence.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Crimeans could no longer expect support from the Ottomans. Şahin's reforms proceeded, gradually removing Tatars from positions of political influence.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] For a brief period, Crimea remained peaceful.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] A new rebellion, sparked by the continuing marginalisation of Tatars within the khanate government, started in 1781.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Various clan leaders and their forces came together in the Taman, across the Kerch Strait from Crimea.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] In April 1782, a large portion of Şahin's army defected to the rebels, and joined them in the Taman.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Communication between rebel leaders, including two of Şahin's brothers, and the Crimean administrative elite was ongoing.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Religious (*ulama*) and legal (*kadı*) officials, important parts of the old Ottoman order, openly declared their antipathy for Şahin.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Rebel forces attacked Kaffa on 14 May [O.S.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] 3 May] 1782. Şahin's forces were swiftly defeated, and he was forced to escape to Russian-controlled Kerch.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Rebel leaders elected Şahin's brother Bahadır Giray as Khan, and sent a message to the Ottoman government seeking recognition.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] It was not long, however, before Catherine dispatched Prince Grigory Potemkin to restore Şahin to power.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] No significant opposition was fielded against the invading Russians, and many rebels fled back across the Kerch Strait.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] As such, the Khan was restored to his position in October 1782.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] By this time, however, he had lost the favour of both Crimeans and Catherine.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] In a letter to a Russian advisor to Şahin, Catherine wrote "He must stop this shocking and cruel treatment and not give them [Crimeans] just cause for a new revolt".
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] As Russian troops entered the peninsula, work began to establish a Black Sea warm-water port for the Empire.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The city of Akitar (modern day Sevastopol) was chosen as the site of the port, which would go on to house the newly created Black Sea Fleet.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Uncertainty about the sustainability of the restoration of Şahin Giray, however, led to an increase of support for annexing Crimea, spearheaded by Potemkin.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] In March 1783, Potemkin made a rhetorical push to encourage Catherine to annex Crimea.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Having just returned from Crimea, he told her that many Crimeans would "happily" submit to Russian rule.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Encouraged by this news, Catherine issued a formal proclamation of annexation on 19 April [O.S.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] 8 April] 1783; Şahin formally relinquished his claim to the khanate.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The Tatars did not resist the annexation; after years of turmoil, the Crimeans lacked the resources and the will to continue fighting.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Many fled the peninsula, leaving for Anatolia.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Tens of thousands of these emigrants took up residence in Constantinople, where they formed an influential exile community, lobbying the Ottoman government to reclaim their Crimean homeland.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Crimean "independence" had been a puppet regime, and the Ottomans had played little role in the Crimean revolts.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The Ottomans went on to recognise the loss of Crimea and other territories that had been held by the khanate in an agreement negotiated by Russian diplomat Yakov Bulgakov.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Known as the Treaty of Constantinople, it was signed on 28 December 1783 [O.S.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Crimea was formally incorporated into the Empire as "Taurida Oblast" during 1784, with Potemkin serving as its first governor.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Catherine visited her newly-claimed territories in an elaborate tour during 1787.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The annexation brought an end to the Crimean slave trade, and marked the beginning of Russian-imposed de-Tatarisation of Crimea.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Following his appointment as governor of the region, Potemkin moved to expropriate Tatar land and assign it to Russian nobles, sparking another wave of Tatar emigration.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] In 1787, Potemkin even urged of the need to curb the Tatar flight due to the negative economic impact it was having on the region, but this proved unfruitful.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The Ottomans would attempt to reclaim Crimea in the Russo-Turkish War of 1787–1792, but were defeated and forced to again acknowledge Russian rule in the Treaty of Jassy.
[src:crimean-war/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] This spurred a mass exodus of Tatars from Crimea; an estimate by Arsenii Markevich suggests that the Tatar population declined from approximately 300,000 at the time of the annexation to 170,000–180,000 in the aftermath of the 1792 treaty.
[src:crimean-war/1854-bombardment-of-odessa] The **Bombardment of Odessa** was an action during the Crimean War in which a joint Anglo-French squadron of warships attacked the Russian port of Odessa.
[src:crimean-war/1854-bombardment-of-odessa] On 6 April 1854, soon after the declaration of war by Britain and France on Russia, the British steam frigate *Furious*, under the command of Captain William Loring, sailed to Odessa and sent a boat into the port under a flag of truce to collect the British Consul there.
[src:crimean-war/1854-bombardment-of-odessa] When leaving the port the boat was fired upon by the Russians.
[src:crimean-war/1854-bombardment-of-odessa] The British naval commander Vice-Admiral James Dundas demanded an explanation from Lieutenant-General Dmitri Osten-Sacken, the military governor of Odessa, for this breach of the laws of war.
[src:crimean-war/1854-bombardment-of-odessa] His reply was considered unacceptable, so a squadron was quickly selected to mount a punitive expedition.
[src:crimean-war/1854-bombardment-of-odessa] Marx also pointed out the "ridiculousness" of the Allies requiring such justifications for launching an attack on an enemy naval base in a time of war.
[src:crimean-war/1854-bombardment-of-odessa] There were also six ship's boats armed with 24-pounder rockets; two from *Britannia*, and one each from *Agamemnon*, *Trafalgar*, *Sans Pareil* and *Highflyer*.
[src:crimean-war/1854-bombardment-of-odessa] On 22 April the Anglo-French fleet arrived off Odessa, and lay offshore.
[src:crimean-war/1854-bombardment-of-odessa] At 5 a.m. the first division (*Descartes*, *Sampson*, *Tiger* and *Vauban*) sailed in, and opened fire on the Russian positions from a range of about 2,000 yards (1,800 m), though with little effect.
[src:crimean-war/1854-bombardment-of-odessa] *Vauban* was hit by a red-hot shot that started a fire aboard and was obliged to temporarily withdraw.
[src:crimean-war/1854-bombardment-of-odessa] She soon returned, bringing the screw corvette *Caton* with her.
[src:crimean-war/1854-bombardment-of-odessa] The second division (*Furious*, *Terrible*, *Retribution* and *Mogador*) then joined the attack, while *Arethusa*, *Highflyer* and *Sans Pareil* remained further offshore as a reserve.
[src:crimean-war/1854-bombardment-of-odessa] The attacking ships now anchored closer in, and it was not long before a shot from *Terrible* hit a magazine on the Imperial Mole, which exploded causing great damage.
[src:crimean-war/1854-bombardment-of-odessa] About 24 Russian ships in the military port were set on fire, and several British and French merchant ships detained there took advantage of the confusion to escape.
[src:crimean-war/1854-bombardment-of-odessa] Meanwhile, the rocket-boats set fire to the dockyard storehouses.
[src:crimean-war/1854-bombardment-of-odessa] Late in the action the *Arethusa*, under the command of Captain William Robert Mends, engaged batteries on the south side of the Quarantine Mole, until recalled.
[src:crimean-war/1854-bombardment-of-odessa] As numerous fires were now threatening the town, the attack was ended at 5.30 p.m., and the squadron withdrew.
[src:crimean-war/1854-bombardment-of-odessa] Casualties were very light; two killed and one wounded in *Vauban*, three wounded in *Retribution*, six wounded in *Sampson*, and one killed and four wounded in *Terrible*.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The **Soviet invasion of Ukraine** was a major offensive by the Ukrainian Front of the Red Army against the Ukrainian People's Republic (UPR) during the Soviet–Ukrainian War.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion was first planned in November 1918, after the Council of People's Commissars of the Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic annulled the Treaty of Brest-Litovsk, and was launched in the first days of January 1919 with the occupation of Kharkiv.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] Its aim was to join Ukraine to the RSFSR, as the country was of significant economic, demographic and strategic importance for the Bolsheviks.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] In the longer term, the capture of the Black Sea coast was to prevent an intervention by the Allies in support of the Volunteer Army.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] Finally, the Bolsheviks intended to extend the area they control as far as possible to the west, in order to be able to support the other revolutionary movements in Europe.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] In the first days of January 1919, by joining forces with local workers' units, the troops of the 1st Ukrainian Soviet Division took Kharkiv, which was announced as the seat of the Provisional Workers' and Peasants' Government of Ukraine.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] Then they quickly captured most of northern and eastern Ukraine, and on 5 February 1919, they occupied Kyiv.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The Directorate of Ukraine moved to Vinnytsia, then to Kamianets-Podilskyi.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] By spring, the Red Army had reached the Zbruch and repelled a counteroffensive by the Ukrainian People's Army (UPA) that threatened Kyiv.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The introduction of the policy of war communism and the requisitioning of food for the needs of the cities quickly alienated a significant part of the Ukrainian peasantry from Bolshevik rule.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The outbreak of a number of local uprisings, and in May 1919, the rebellion of the 20,000-strong forces of Nykyfor Hryhoriv, prevented the Red Army from finally destroying the UPA and marching west towards Bessarabia and Hungary.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] At the end of June, the Red Army suffered a series of defeats in clashes with the Volunteer Army in Donbas, losing Katerynoslav and Poltava by the end of June 1919, as well as those territories captured in the course of operations against Mykolaiv and Odesa.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] In August, the Red Army also succumbed to the offensive of the combined forces of the Ukrainian People's Army and the Ukrainian Galician Army.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] On 31 August, Kyiv was captured, first by the Ukrainian People's Army, and then, after their withdrawal from the city, by the Volunteer Army.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The Ukrainian Revolutionary Military Council was immediately established, including Antonov-Ovseenko, Joseph Stalin, Volodymyr Zatonsky and Georgy Pyatakov.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] Over the next two days, Antonov-Ovseenko developed an offensive plan.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] It was based on the assumption that, in the first place, the Bolshevik forces should seize cities, industrial centers, ports, and railway junctions, which would provide the necessary resources and guarantee the possibility of gaining support from the workers.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] In the first move, Antonov-Ovseenko planned to attack Kharkiv, which would then become the base for the march to Donbas.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The second step was to capture Kyiv, and the third step was to capture southern Ukraine and the Black Sea coast, including the key centers of Mykolaiv and Odesa.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] As the commander-in-chief of the Red Army Jukums Vācietis adopted the Antonov-Ovseenko plan without amendments, he decided that he would receive in the course of operations all the necessary replenishment (including armored trains) and supplies.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] In particular, the commander of the Ukrainian Front expected that he would have at his disposal the Reserve Army under the command of Vasily Glagolev.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] Vacietis, however, assigned him completely different tasks - participation in the defense of Voronezh against Pyotr Krasnov's Don Army and Anton Denikin's Volunteer Army.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] An additional source of conflicts between Vacietis and the Ukrainian Revolutionary-Military Council was the conviction of Stalin, Zatonsky and Pyatakov that they were performing a task of special importance, independent of other operations conducted by the Southern Front.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] At the disposal of Antonov-Ovseenko were initially the 1st and 2nd Ukrainian Soviet Divisions, as well as the 9th division, to which new volunteers were constantly arriving, but which needed urgent additions to hardware and supplies.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The two Soviet Ukrainian divisions, formed in mid-1918 by the Ukrainian Bolsheviks in order to fight the government of Pavlo Skoropadskyi and the Central Powers, did not have high combat value.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] Many volunteers who joined them during the formation intended to fight only in their local area and deserted when the fighting moved to other regions.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] On 20 November, Antonov-Ovseenko directed orders both to the line units of the Red Army and to irregular units in Ukraine that were participating in the anti-Hetman uprising and recognizing, at least formally, the sovereignty of the All-Ukrainian Central Military-Revolutionary Committee.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] He ordered the revolutionary troops in Homiel to maintain control of the city in order to prevent anti-Bolshevik forces from moving from Kyiv towards Kursk and Bryansk.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] Those operating in the regions of Katerynoslav and Kharkiv were ordered to initiate local revolts, take control of smaller towns in order to facilitate the Red Army's march south, help in the capture of Kharkiv and, in the longer term, Mykolaiv.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] Bolshevik supporters in northern Donbas were called on to organize guerrillas and take control of the region, and those who were in Crimea - to prepare to repel possible Allied intervention on the peninsula.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] In November 1918, a wave of strikes broke out in cities in eastern Ukraine and partisan troops also operated outside the cities.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] Meanwhile, on 21 November, Vacietis ordered Antonov-Ovseenko to focus on the expansion and training of troops and to set up a strike group that would attack the forces of Pyotr Krasnov at Millerovo.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] Troops of the Don Cossacks, with the consent of the retreating Germans, took control of the Donbas from them.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The commander of the Ukrainian Front decided to ignore the orders of the high command, offended by the tone and wording contained in the Vacietis directives.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] Having learned about the landing of the first Allied ships in Odesa, Antonov-Ovseenko decided to lead the offensive according to his own concept.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] At the same time, Pyatakov and Zatonsky began to form a Bolshevik government for Ukraine.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] However, it was decided to undertake military intervention.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] On 28 November 1918, the Provisional Workers' and Peasants' Government of Ukraine was established in Kursk.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] In December 1918, the Ukrainian Soviet divisions were put at the disposal of Antonov-Ovseenko.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] Numbering approximately 5,000 soldiers each, the divisions were still not full-fledged regular formations.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] They consisted of undisciplined, largely independent departments.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] Their commanders included both ideological communists and ordinary peasants.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] One-third of the red soldiers and guerrillas had no weapons at all.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] Before the start of military operations, Antonov-Ovseenko relieved the most disgraced commanders from command, but he never gained complete control over the units that made up his front.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] Further disputes between Antonov-Ovseenko and Vacietis concerning competences and tactics lasted almost throughout December 1918.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] Finally, on 2 January 1919, Antonov-Ovseenko made a decision on his own to start the march to Kharkiv, having learned that the last German units were withdrawing from the city and that the Bolshevik workers' units were getting ready to start an armed uprising.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] On 3 January 1919, the 1st Ukrainian Soviet Division entered Kharkiv.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The next day, the Ukrainian Front was formally established with Antonov-Ovseenko as the commander.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The Reserve Army was attached to the Front, and Vasily Glagolev was appointed as its chief of staff.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] A significant part of the partisan peasant units in Ukraine, which had previously fought against the Germans and sympathized with Petliura, defected to the Soviet side, under the influence of Bolshevik agitation.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The urban proletariat of non-Ukrainian origin also joined the fight on the side of the Red Army.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] After the capture of Kharkiv, the offensive of the Ukrainian Front significantly accelerated.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] On 12 January 1919, the Red Army captured Chernihiv and, on 20 January, it successfully captured Poltava after a sixteen-day battle for the city.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] Units of the 2nd Ukrainian Soviet Division, led by Pavel Dybenko, entered Katerynoslav, which the Petliurists and Makhnovists had been fighting fiercely over.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] On 18 January 1919, Antonov-Ovseenko, who moved his quarters from Kursk to Chernihiv, accelerated the preparations for the march to Kyiv.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] He expected that the Allies who landed in Odesa and Crimea also intended to launch an offensive in the same direction, in support of Anton Denikin's Volunteer Army.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] However, the negotiations of the Directorate with the French regarding active military aid ended with the French refusing.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] In the face of the invasion, treating the Red Army's march as an expression of Russian imperialism, Vynnychenko's Ukrainian socialists supported the defense of the country's independence.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] However, it turned out to be impossible to successfully repel the march of the Ukrainian Front, as the forces loyal to the Directorate were dwindling with each passing day.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The Ukrainian national movement did not have a broad social base, being the domain of mainly a narrow intelligentsia.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] In addition, the Directorate was weakened by internal disputes between nationalists and socialists.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] At the end of January, only 21,000 soldiers remained loyal to the Ukrainian government.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] On 23 January, Symon Petliura began the evacuation of military personnel from the capital to avoid a battle, the outcome of which would be a foregone conclusion.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] Meanwhile, the Bolshevik troops continued to grow, after the occupation of Kharkiv, as the 1st Ukrainian Soviet Division alone reached over 10,000 soldiers.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The Ukrainian capital was left without a fight, seized by the 1st Ukrainian Soviet Division on 5 February.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] Earlier, on 29 January 1919, the Provisional Workers' and Peasants Government was transformed into the Council of People's Commissars, headed by Christian Rakovsky.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The directorate moved to Vinnytsia, and then to Kamianets-Podilskyi.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] By the end of January, the Red Army had captured the entirety of left-bank Ukraine.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] In early February, partisan units allied with the Red Army seized Znamianka, Kryvyi Rih and Dovhyntseve.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] A workers' uprising broke out in Yelysavethrad, the participants of which, after joining forces with the partisans, seized the city.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] On 12 February, Novomyrhorod was seized.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The Red Army continued their march south and west into areas controlled by Allied interventionist troops.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] By this time, there were 200,000 people in the Red Army, as the anarchist forces of Nestor Makhno were incorporated into the Ukrainian Soviet ranks and the peasant division of otaman Nykyfor Hryhoriv also defected from the side of the Ukrainian nationalists to the Soviets.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] After the capture of Kyiv, the Red Army continued its offensive actions in three directions.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The Northern Group headed from Mazyr towards Korosten, and from Luninets through Sarny towards Rivne, to prevent the Ukrainian People's Army from joining forces with the Ukrainian Galician Army.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The Southern Group, supported by the forces of otaman Hryhoriv, was intended to cut off the UPA troops from possible Allied aid and attacked from the Katerynoslav region and Kremenchuk along the line Zhmerynka-Koziatyn-Podilsk.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The third group headed from Kyiv along the Berdychiv-Koziatyn-Zhmerynka line to prevent the northern and southern wings of the Ukrainian People's Republic from joining.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian troops survived in Volhynia and Podolia, but the existence of the Ukrainian People's Republic, at the same time at war with Poland, and cut off from the Black Sea from the south by French forces, seemed doomed.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] By mid-February, there were 46,000 soldiers and 14 thousand partisans under the command of Antonov-Ovseenko.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The regular army, however, still remained insufficiently disciplined and trained, lacked competent officers and political commissars.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] In turn, the loyalty of partisan formations to the Bolshevik command was uncertain, these units repeatedly robbed and murdered Jews, or even local newly arrived Soviet officials.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] In the spring of 1919, the army of the Ukrainian People's Republic withdrew to the vicinity of Kamianets-Podilskyi and western Volhynia, and the Red Army had reached the Zbruch.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The implementation of war communism by the government of Rakovsky, which introduced requisitions and the Cheka to the countryside, quickly alienated a significant part of the Ukrainian peasantry from the Bolshevik rule.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] Rakovsky was also reluctant to cooperate with the Borotbists, who acted independently of the Bolshevik party.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] As a result, there was a series of peasant uprisings in the countryside against the new authorities.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The reorganization of the Ukrainian Soviet government and the introduction of Borotbist representatives into it only partially calmed the situation.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] Party officials and activists from Moscow, not understanding the local realities, contributed to the growth of antagonisms.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] In March 1919, the Ukrainian People's Army launched a counteroffensive, defeating the Red Army along the Koziatyn-Berdychiv line.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] It came close to achieving its goal of regaining Kyiv.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] In April, the Red Army launched a counter-attack, seizing Zhmerynka and cutting off the southern flank of the Ukrainian People's Army from its core body.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The Ukrainian People's Army was pushed to a narrow strip of territory, with an average width of 40-50 km, in the Brody and Dubno region.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] An attempted coup by Volodymyr Oskilko weakened it all the more.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] In May 1919, the most serious uprising against the Soviet government in central and southern Ukraine took place - otaman Nykyfor Hryhoriv led a rebellion against the command of the Ukrainian Front and the government of the Ukrainian SSR.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] His forces numbered 20,000 soldiers, 10 armored trains and 700 machine guns, which allowed him to take control of the area with Katerynoslav, Yelysavethrad, Kherson, Kremenchuk, Mykolaiv, Cherkasy, Oleksandriia and Kryvyi Rih.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The necessity to fight Hryhoriv forced the command of the Ukrainian Front to give up any further offensive in the south-west direction, making it impossible to enter Bessarabia and Eastern Galicia and preventing them from providing military support to the Hungarian Soviet Republic.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] In June 1919, after the conclusion of a ceasefire with Poland and regrouping, the Ukrainian People's Army numbered 15,000 active soldiers.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] At the beginning of the month, it again took control of Podolia.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] At the end of the month, the Red Army achieved a new victory, taking Proskuriv and approaching Kamianets-Podilskyi.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The Ukrainian People's Army achieved a new success when it was joined by Yuriy Tyutyunnyk's troops, which had previously been under the command of Hryhoriv.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The Ukrainian counter-offensive reached the line Horodok-Jarmolińce-Szarhorod-Dunajowce-Nowa Uszyca-Wapniarka.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] This was followed by the merger of the Ukrainian People's Army with the Ukrainian Galician Army, which brought together 85,000 soldiers and 15,000 partisans.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] At the same time, the Red Army suffered a series of defeats in the fight against the Volunteer Army.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] At the beginning of June, it lost in the battle for the Donbas.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] By 27 June, the Ukrainian Soviet capital of Kharkiv was lost to the Whites.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The following day, Katerynoslav also fell to the White advance, followed soon after by Poltava, Mykolaiv and Odesa.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] In August 1919, the Ukrainian troops carried out a successful offensive in the direction of Kyiv, successively taking Vinnytsia on 12 August, Starokostiantyniv on 14 August, Berdychiv on 19 August and Zhytomyr on 21 August.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] On 31 August, the Ukrainian Galician troops of Myron Tarnavsky briefly entered Kyiv, which had been abandoned by the Bolsheviks, but a few hours later White troops led by Nikolai Bredov occupied the city.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] As the bridges on the Dniepr were not manned by the Ukrainian troops, they were forced to hand the city over to the Whites.
[src:crimean-war/1919-soviet-invasion-of-ukraine] The conflict between the Ukrainian nationalists and the Whites made it possible for the Bolsheviks to transfer some of their forces from the Katerynoslav region to right-bank Ukraine, near Zhytomyr, and to continue fighting with Petliura's forces.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] A popular uprising by Palestinian Arabs in Mandatory Palestine against the British administration, known as the **Great Revolt**, and later the **Great Palestinian Revolt** or the **Palestinian Revolution**, lasted from 1936 until 1939.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The movement sought independence from British colonial rule and the end of British support for Zionism, including Jewish immigration and land sales to Jews.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The uprising occurred during a peak in the influx of European Jewish immigrants, and with the growing plight of the rural fellahin rendered landless, who as they moved to metropolitan centres to escape their abject poverty found themselves socially marginalized.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] A month into the disturbances, Amin al-Husseini, president of the Arab Higher Committee and Mufti of Jerusalem, declared 16 May 1936 as "Palestine Day" and called for a general strike.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] David Ben-Gurion, leader of the Yishuv, described Arab causes as fear of growing Jewish economic power, opposition to mass Jewish immigration and fear of the British identification with Zionism.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The general strike lasted from April to October 1936.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The revolt is often analysed in terms of two distinct phases.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The first phase began as spontaneous popular resistance, which was seized on by the urban bourgeois Arab Higher Committee, giving the movement an organized shape that was focused mainly on strikes and other forms of political protest, in order to secure a political result.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] By October 1936, this phase had been defeated by the British civil administration using a combination of political concessions, international diplomacy (involving the rulers of Iraq, Saudi Arabia, Transjordan and Yemen) and the threat of martial law.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The second phase, which began late in 1937, was a peasant-led resistance movement provoked by British repression in 1936 in which increasingly British forces were targeted as the army itself increasingly targeted the villages it thought supportive of the revolt.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] During this phase, the rebellion was brutally suppressed by the British Army and the Palestine Police Force using repressive measures that were intended to intimidate the whole population and undermine popular support for the revolt.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] According to official British figures covering the whole revolt, the army and police killed more than 2,000 Arabs in combat, 108 were hanged, and 961 died because of what they described as "gang and terrorist activities".
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] In an analysis of the British statistics, Walid Khalidi estimates 19,792 casualties for the Arabs, with 5,032 dead: 3,832 killed by the British and 1,200 dead due to intracommunal terrorism, and 14,760 wounded.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] By one estimate, ten percent of the adult male Palestinian Arab population between 20 and 60 was killed, wounded, imprisoned or exiled.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Estimates of the number of Palestinian Jews killed are up to several hundred.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The Arab revolt in Mandatory Palestine was unsuccessful, and its consequences affected the outcome of the 1948 Palestine war.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] It caused the British Mandate to give crucial support to pre-state Zionist militias like the Haganah, whereas on the Palestinian Arab side, the revolt forced the main Palestinian Arab leader of the period, al-Husseini, into exile.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] World War I left Palestine, especially the countryside, deeply impoverished.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The Ottoman and then the Mandate authorities levied high taxes on farming and agricultural produce and during the 1920s and 1930s this together with a fall in prices, cheap imports, natural disasters and paltry harvests all contributed to the increasing indebtedness of the fellahin.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] By 1931 the 106,400 dunums of low-lying Category A farming land in Arab possession supported a farming population of 590,000 whereas the 102,000 dunums of such land in Jewish possession supported a farming population of only 50,000.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The late 1920s witnessed poor harvests, and the consequent immiseration grew even harsher with the onset of the Great Depression and the collapse of commodity prices.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Economic factors played a major role in the outbreak of the Arab revolt.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Palestine's fellahin, the country's peasant farmers, made up over two-thirds of the indigenous Arab population and from the 1920s onwards they were pushed off the land in increasingly large numbers into urban environments where they often encountered only poverty and social marginalisation.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Many were crowded into shanty towns in Jaffa and Haifa where some found succour and encouragement in the teachings of the charismatic preacher Izz ad-Din al-Qassam who worked among the poor in Haifa.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The revolt was thus a popular uprising that produced its own leaders and developed into a national revolt.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Although the Mandatory government introduced measures to limit the transfer of land from Arabs to Jews, these were easily circumvented by willing buyers and sellers.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The failure of the authorities to invest in economic growth and healthcare for the general Palestinian public and the Zionist policy of ensuring that their investments were directed only to facilitate expansion exclusively of the Yishuv further compounded matters.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] After 1935 the slump in the construction boom and further concentration by the Yishuv on an exclusivist Hebrew labour programme removed most of the sources of employment for rural migrants.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] By 1935 only 12,000 Arabs (5% of the workforce) worked in the Jewish sector, half of these in agriculture, whereas 32,000 worked for the Mandate authorities and 211,000 were either self-employed or worked for Arab employers.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] At the same time, Jewish immigration peaked in 1935, just months before Palestinian Arabs began their full-scale, nationwide revolt.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] In 1936 alone, some 60,000 Jews immigrated that year – the Jewish population having grown under British auspices from 57,000 to 320,000 in 1935.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The advent of Zionism and British colonial administration crystallised Palestinian nationalism and the desire to defend indigenous traditions and institutions.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Palestinian society was largely clan-based (*hamula*), with an urban land-holding elite lacking a centralised leadership.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The expansion of education, the development of civil society and of transportation, communications, and especially of broadcasting and other media, all facilitated notable changes.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The Yishuv itself, at the same time, was steadily building the structures for its own state-building with public organisations like the Jewish Agency and the covert creation and consolidation of a paramilitary arm with the Haganah and Irgun.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] In 1930 Sheikh Izz ad-Din al-Qassam organised and established the Black Hand, a small anti-Zionist and anti-British militia.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] He recruited and arranged military training for impoverished but pious peasants but also for ex-criminals he had persuaded to take Islam seriously and they engaged in a campaign of vandalizing tree plantations and British-constructed rail lines, destroying phone lines and disrupting transportation.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The pressures of the 1930s wrought several changes, giving rise to new political organizations and a broader activism that spurred a far wider cross-section of the population in rural areas, strongly nationalist, to join actively in the Palestinian cause.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Youth organisations emerged like Young Men's Muslim Association and the Youth Congress Party, the former anti-Zionist, the latter pan-Arab.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The Palestinian Boy Scout Movement, founded early in 1936, became active in the general strike.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Myriads of rural women would play an important role in response to *faz'a* alarm calls for inter-village help by rallying in defence of the rebellion.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] General strikes had been used in neighbouring Arab countries to place political pressures on Western colonial powers.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] In Iraq a general strike in July 1931, accompanied by organised demonstrations in the streets, led to independence for the former British mandate territory under Prime Minister Nuri as-Said, and full membership of the League of Nations in October 1932.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The Syrian National Bloc had used a general strike from 20 January to 6 March in 1936 which, despite harsh reprisals, brought about negotiations in Paris that led to a Franco-Syrian Treaty of Independence.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] This showed that determined economic and political pressure could challenge a fragile imperial administration.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] On 16 October 1935 a large arms shipment camouflaged in cement bins, comprising 25 Lewis guns and their bipods, 800 rifles and 400,000 rounds of ammunition destined for the Haganah, was discovered during unloading at the port of Jaffa.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The news sparked Arab fears of a Jewish military takeover of Palestine.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] A little over two weeks later, on 2 November 1935, al-Qassam gave a speech in the port of Haifa denouncing the Balfour declaration on its 18th anniversary.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] In a proclamation to that effect, together with Jamal al-Husayni, he alluded to the Haganah weapons smuggling operation.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Questioned at the time by a confidant about his preparations, he stated that he had 15 men, each furnished with a rifle and one cartridge.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Soon after, perhaps fearing a pending preemptive arrest, he disappeared with his group into the hills, not to start a revolution, premature at that point, but to impress upon people that he was a man ready to do what he said should be done.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Some weeks later, a Jewish policeman was shot dead in a citrus grove while investigating the theft of grapefruit, after he happened to come close to the Qassamites' encampment.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Following the incident, the Palestine police launched a massive manhunt and surrounded al-Qassam in a cave just north of Ya'bad.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] In the ensuing battle, on 20 November, al-Qassam was killed.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The death of al-Qassam generated widespread outrage among Palestinian Arabs, galvanizing public sentiments with an impact similar to the effect on the Yishuv of news of the death of Joseph Trumpeldor in 1920 at the Tel Hai settlement.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Huge crowds gathered for the occasion of his obsequies in Haifa and later burial in Balad al-Shaykh.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] One of the three, Israel Chazan, was from Thessaloniki.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The Salonican community's request that permission be granted to allow them to conduct a solemn funeral for Chasan was turned down by the district commissioner, who had allowed al-Qassam a ceremonial burial some months earlier.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The refusal sparked a demonstration by 30,000 Jews in Tel Aviv who overcame the police and maltreated Arab labourers and damaged property in Jaffa.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The following day, two Arab workers sleeping in a hut in a banana plantation beside the highway between Petah Tikva and Yarkona were assassinated in retaliation by members of the Haganah-Bet.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Jews and Palestinians attacked each other in and around Tel Aviv.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Palestinians in Jaffa rampaged through a Jewish residential area, resulting in several Jewish deaths.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] After four days, by 19 April, the deteriorating situation erupted into a set of countrywide disturbances.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] An Arab general strike and revolt ensued that lasted until October 1936.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The strike began on 19 April in Nablus, where an Arab National Committee was formed, and by the end of the month National Committees had been formed in all of the towns and some of the larger villages.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] On the same day, the High Commissioner Wauchope issued Emergency Regulations that laid the legal basis for suppressing the insurgency.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] On 21 April the leaders of the five main parties accepted the decision at Nablus and called for a general strike of all Arabs engaged in labour, transport and shopkeeping for the following day.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] While the strike was initially organised by workers and local committees, under pressure from below, political leaders became involved to help with co-ordination.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] This led to the formation on 25 April 1936 of the Arab Higher Committee (AHC).
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] About one month after the general strike started, the leadership group declared a general non-payment of taxes in explicit opposition to Jewish immigration.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] In the countryside, armed insurrection started sporadically, becoming more organized over time.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] One particular target of the rebels was the Mosul–Haifa oil pipeline of the Iraq Petroleum Company constructed only a few years earlier to Haifa from a point on the Jordan River south of Lake Tiberias.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] This was repeatedly bombed at various points along its length.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Other attacks were on railways (including trains) and on civilian targets such as Jewish settlements, secluded Jewish neighbourhoods in the mixed cities, and Jews, both individually and in groups.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] During the summer of that year, thousands of Jewish-farmed acres and orchards were destroyed, Jewish civilians were attacked and murdered, and some Jewish communities, such as those in Beisan and Acre, fled to safer areas.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The measures taken against the strike were harsh from the outset and grew harsher as the revolt deepened.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Unable to contain the protests with the two battalions already stationed in the country, Britain inundated Palestine with soldiers from regiments all over the empire, including its Egyptian garrison.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The drastic measures taken included house searches without warrants, night raids, preventive detention, caning, flogging, deportation, confiscation of property, and torture.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] As early as May 1936 the British formed armed Jewish units equipped with armoured vehicles to serve as auxiliary police.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] In reality the measures created a sense of solidarity between the villagers and the rebels.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] On 2 June, an attempt by rebels to derail a train bringing the 2nd Battalion Bedfordshire and Hertfordshire Regiment from Egypt led to the railways being put under guard, placing a great strain on the security forces.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] On 4 June, in response to this situation, the government rounded up a large number of Palestinian leaders and sent them to a detention camp at Auja al-Hafir in the Negev desert.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The Battle of Nur Shams on 21 June marked an escalation with the largest engagement of British troops against Arab militants so far in this Revolt.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] During July, Arab volunteers from Syria and Transjordan, led by Fawzi al-Qawukji, helped the rebels to divide their formations into four fronts, each led by a District Commander who had armed platoons of 150–200 fighters, each commanded by a platoon leader.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] A Statement of Policy issued by the Colonial Office in London on 7 September declared the situation a "direct challenge to the authority of the British Government in Palestine" and announced the appointment of Lieutenant-General John Dill as supreme military commander.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] By the end of September 20,000 British troops in Palestine were deployed to "round up Arab bands".
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] In June 1936 the British involved their clients in Transjordan, Iraq, Saudi Arabia and Egypt in an attempt to pacify the Palestinian Arabs and on 9 October the rulers made an appeal for the strike to be ended.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] A more pressing concern may have been the approaching citrus harvest and the attractive, soaring prices on the international markets caused by the disruption to the Spanish citrus harvest due to the Spanish Civil War.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] On 22 August 1936, Anglo-Jewish Arabist scholar Levi Billig of Hebrew University was murdered in his home outside Jerusalem by an Arab assassin, one of three Jews killed by Arabs on 22 August, and one of 73 Jews killed since the beginning of the Arab armed insurrection.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The strike was called off on 11 October 1936 and the violence abated for about a year while the Peel Commission deliberated.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The Royal Commission was announced on 18 May 1936 and its members were appointed on 29 July, but the Commission did not arrive in Palestine until 11 November.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] In the early 1920s the first High Commissioner of Palestine, Herbert Samuel, had failed to create a unified political structure embracing both Palestinian Arabs and Palestinian Jews in constitutional government with joint political institutions.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] This failure facilitated internal institutional partition in which the Jewish Agency exercised a degree of autonomous control over the Jewish settlement and the Supreme Muslim Council performed a comparable role for Muslims.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Thus, well before Lord Peel arrived in Palestine on 11 November 1936, the groundwork for territorial partition as proposed by the Royal Commission in its report on 7 July 1937 had already been done.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Peel's main recommendation was for partition of Palestine into a small Jewish state (based on current Jewish land ownership population and incorporating the country's most productive agricultural land), a residual Mandatory area, and a larger Arab state linked to Transjordan.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] A second and more radical proposal was for transfer of 225,000 Palestinian Arabs from the proposed Jewish state to a future Arab state and Transjordan.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] It is likely that Zionist leaders played a role in persuading Peel to accept the notion of transfer, which had been a strand of Zionist ideology from its inception.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The Arab Higher Committee rejected the recommendations immediately, as did the Jewish Revisionists.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Initially, the religious Zionists, some of the General Zionists, and sections of the Labour Zionist movement also opposed the recommendations.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The British government initially accepted the Peel report in principle.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] However, with war clouds looming over Europe, they realized that to attempt to implement it against the will of the Palestinian Arab majority would rouse up the entire Arab world against Britain.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The Woodhead Commission considered three different plans, one of which was based on the Peel plan.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Reporting in 1938, the Commission rejected the Peel plan primarily on the grounds that it could not be implemented without a massive forced transfer of Arabs (an option that the British government had already ruled out).
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] With dissent from some of its members, the Commission instead recommended a plan that would leave the Galilee under British mandate, but emphasised serious problems with it that included a lack of financial self-sufficiency of the proposed Arab State.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The British Government accompanied the publication of the Woodhead Report by a statement of policy rejecting partition as impracticable due to "political, administrative and financial difficulties".
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] With the failure of the Peel Commission's proposals the revolt resumed during the autumn of 1937 marked by the assassination on 26 September of Acting District Commissioner of the Galilee Lewis Andrews by Quassemite gunmen in Nazareth.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Andrews was widely hated by Palestinians for supporting Jewish settlement in the Galilee, and he openly advised Jews to create their own defense force.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] On 30 September, regulations were issued allowing the Government to detain political deportees in any part of the British Empire, and authorising the High Commissioner to outlaw associations whose objectives he regarded as contrary to public policy.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] In November 1937, the Irgun formally rejected the policy of Havlagah and embarked on a series of indiscriminate attacks against Arab civilians as a form of what the group called "active defense" against Arab attacks on Jewish civilians.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The British authorities set up military courts, which were established for the trial of offenses connected with the carrying and discharge of firearms, sabotage and intimidation.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Despite this, however, the Arab campaign of murder and sabotage continued and Arab gangs in the hills took on the appearance of organised guerrilla fighters.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] In July 1938, when the Palestine Government seemed to have largely lost control of the situation, the garrison was strengthened from Egypt, and in September it was further reinforced from England.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The police were placed under the operational control of the army commander, and military officials superseded the civil authorities in the enforcement of order.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] In October the Old City of Jerusalem, which had become a rebel stronghold, was reoccupied by the troops.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] By the end of the year a semblance of order had been restored in the towns, but terrorism continued in rural areas until the outbreak of the Second World War.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Despite cooperation of the Yishuv with the British to quell the revolt, some incidents towards the end of the conflict indicated a coming change in relations.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] On 12 June 1939, A British explosives expert was killed trying to defuse an Irgun bomb near a Jerusalem post office.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] On 26 August, two British police officers, Inspector Ronald Barker and Inspector Ralph Cairns, commander of the Jewish Department of the C.I.D., were killed by an Irgun mine in Jerusalem.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Military law allowed swift prison sentences to be passed.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Thousands of Arabs were held in administrative detention, without trial, and without proper sanitation, in overcrowded prison camps.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The British had already formalised the principle of collective punishment in Palestine in the 1924–1925 Collective Responsibility and Punishment Ordinances and updated these ordinances in 1936 with the Collective Fines Ordinance.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Following the Arab capture of the Old City of Jerusalem in October 1938, the army effectively took over Jerusalem and then all of Palestine.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The main form of collective punishment employed by the British forces was destruction of property.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Sometimes entire villages were reduced to rubble, as happened to Mi'ar in October 1938; more often several prominent houses were blown up and others were trashed inside.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The biggest single act of destruction occurred in Jaffa on 16 June 1936, when large gelignite charges were used to cut long pathways through the old city, destroying 220–240 buildings and rendering up to 6,000 Arabs homeless.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Scathing criticism for this action from Palestine Chief Justice Sir Michael McDonnell was not well received by the administration and the judge was soon removed from the country.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Villages were also frequently punished by fines and confiscation of livestock.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The British even used sea mines from the battleship HMS *Malaya* to destroy houses.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In addition to actions against property, a large amount of brutality by the British forces occurred, including beatings, torture and extrajudicial killings.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] A surprisingly large number of prisoners were "shot while trying to escape".
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Several incidents involved serious atrocities, such as massacres at al-Bassa and Halhul.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] As well as destroying the village the RUR and men from the Royal Engineers collected around fifty men from al-Bassa and blew some of them up with explosion under a bus.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The other villagers were then forced to bury the bodies in a pit.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The report was issued in response to growing concern at the severity of the military measures amongst the general public in Great Britain, among members of the British Government, and among governments in countries neighbouring Palestine.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In addition to actions against villages the British Army also conducted punitive actions in the cities.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In Nablus in August 1938 almost 5,000 men were held in a cage for two days and interrogated one after another.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] During their detention the city was searched and then each of the detainees was marked with a rubber stamp on his release.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] At one point a night curfew was imposed on most of the cities.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] It was common British army practice to use local Arabs as human shields by forcing them to ride with military convoys to prevent mine attacks and sniping incidents: soldiers would tie the hostages to the bonnets of lorries, or put them on small flatbeds on the front of trains.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The army told the hostages that any of them who tried to run away would be shot.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] British troops also left Arab wounded on the battlefield to die and maltreated Arab fighters taken in battle, so much so that the rebels tried to remove their wounded or dead from the field of battle.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Sometimes, soldiers would occupy villages, expel all of the inhabitants and remain for months.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The Army even burned the bodies of "terrorists" to prevent their funerals becoming the focus of protests.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Sir Charles Tegart was a senior police officer brought into Palestine from the colonial force of British India on 21 October 1937.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Tegart and his deputy David Petrie (later head of MI5) advised a greater emphasis on foreign intelligence gathering and closure of Palestine's borders.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Like many of those enrolled in the Palestinian gendarmerie, Tegart had served in Great Britain's repression of the Irish War of Independence, and the security proposals he introduced exceeded measures adopted down to this time elsewhere in the British Empire.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] 70 fortresses were erected throughout the country at strategic choke points and near Palestinian villages which, if assessed as "bad", were subjected to collective punishment.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Tegart recommended the construction of a frontier road with a barbed wire fence, which became known as Tegart's wall, along the borders with Lebanon and Syria to help prevent the flow of insurgents, goods and weapons.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Tegart encouraged close co-operation with the Jewish Agency.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] It was built by the Histadrut construction company Solel Boneh.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The Army forced the fellahin to work on the roads without pay.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Tegart introduced Arab Investigation Centres where prisoners were subjected to beatings, foot whipping (bastinado), electric shocks, denailing and what is now known as "waterboarding".
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Tegart also imported Doberman Pinschers from South Africa and set up a special centre in Jerusalem to train interrogators in torture.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The Royal Air Force developed close air support into its then most refined form during the Arab Revolt.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Air patrols had been found effective in keeping convoys and trains free from attack, but this did not help to expose insurgents to battle conditions likely to cause their defeat.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] From the middle of June 1936 wireless vehicles accompanied all convoys and patrols.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] During rebel attacks these vehicles could issue emergency "XX calls" (XX with a coded location), which were given priority over all other radio traffic, to summon aerial reinforcements.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Bombers, which were usually airborne within five minutes, could then either attack insurgents directly or "fix" their position for infantry troops.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Forty-seven such XX calls were issued during the revolt, causing heavy losses to the rebels.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In the June 1936 Battle of Nur Shams British planes attacked Arab irregulars with machine gun fire.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] This use of air power was so successful that the British were able to reduce the regular garrison.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In 1936 an Air Staff Officer in Middle East Command based in the Kingdom of Egypt, Arthur Harris, known as an advocate of "air policing", commented on the revolt saying that "one 250 lb. or 500 lb. bomb in each village that speaks out of turn" would satisfactorily solve the problem.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In 1937 Harris was promoted to Air Commodore and in 1938 he was posted to Palestine and Trans-Jordan as Air Officer Commanding the RAF contingent in the region until September 1939.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] "Limited" bombing attacks on Arab villages were carried out by the RAF, although at times this involved razing whole villages.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Harris described the system by which recalcitrant villages were kept under control by aerial bombardment as "Air-Pin".
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Aircraft of the RAF were also used to drop propaganda leaflets over Palestinian towns and villages telling the fellahin that they were the main sufferers of the rebellion and threatening an increase in taxes.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Low flying RAF squadrons were able to produce detailed intelligence on the location of road blocks, sabotaged bridges, railways and pipelines.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] RAF aerial photographs were also used to build up a detailed map of Arab population distribution.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Although the British Army was responsible for setting up the Arab counter-insurgent forces (known as the peace bands) and supplying them with arms and money these were operated by RAF Intelligence, commanded by Patrick Domville.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] At the beginning of the revolt RAF assets in the region comprised a bomber flight at RAF Ramleh, an RAF armoured car flight at Ramleh, fourteen bomber squadrons at RAF Amman, and a RAF armoured car company at Ma'an.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] At the beginning of the Revolt crew from the Haifa Naval Force's two cruisers were used to carry out tasks ashore, manning two howitzers and naval lorries equipped with QF 2 pounder naval guns and searchlights used to disperse Arab snipers.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] From the end of June two destroyers were used to patrol the coast of Palestine in a bid to prevent gun running.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] These searched as many as 150 vessels per week and were an effective preventive measure.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] At the request of the Army additional naval platoons landed in July to help protect Haifa and Jewish settlements in the surrounding countryside.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The Navy also relieved the Army of duties in Haifa by using nine naval platoons to form the *Haifa Town Force* and in August three naval platoons were landed to support the police.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Following publication of the Peel Commission's report in July 1937 HMS *Repulse* sailed to Haifa where landing parties were put ashore to maintain calm.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Various other naval vessels continued with this role until the end of the revolt.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Following the Irgun's detonation of a large bomb in a market in Haifa on 6 July 1938 the High Commissioner signalled the Commander-in-Chief of the Mediterranean Fleet, Admiral Sir Dudley Pound, requesting the assistance of naval vessels capable of providing landing parties.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Pound dispatched HMS *Repulse* and diverted HMS *Emerald* to Haifa, which arrived the same day and landed five platoons, one to each police district.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] HMS *Repulse* relieved HMS *Emerald* the following day and after another bomb was detonated on 10 July five platoons from the ship, made up of sailors and Royal Marines, dispersed mobs and patrolled the city.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] On 11 July provision of three platoons from *Repulse* released men of the West Kent Regiment for a punitive mission against Arabs who had attacked a Jewish colony near Haifa.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] By 17 July the *Repulse* established a Company Headquarters where seamen and Royal Marines manned a 3.7-inch howitzer.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Sailors, Royal Marines, and men of the Suffolk Regiment, who had embarked on the *Repulse*, accompanied foot patrols of the Palestine Police Force.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The *Repulse*, HMS *Hood* and HMS *Warspite* provided howitzer crews which were sent ashore to combat gun running near the border with Lebanon.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Detained Arabs were used to build emplacements and the howitzers were moved quickly between these positions by day and night to confuse bandits as to the likely direction of fire.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Periodically, the guns were used to fire warning rounds close to the vicinity of villages believed to have rebel sympathies.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Britain had completed the modern deep-sea port in Haifa in 1933 and finished laying a pipeline from the Iraqi oilfields to Haifa in 1935, shortly before the outbreak of the revolt.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] A refinery for processing oil from the pipeline was completed by Consolidated Refineries Ltd, a company jointly owned by British Petroleum and Royal Dutch Shell, in December 1939.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] These facilities enhanced the strategic importance of Palestine and of Haifa in particular in Britain's control of the eastern Mediterranean.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The Arab Revolt was the last major test of Britain's security services in the Middle East before World War II.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The rebellion had brought together urban nationalism and peasant economic grievances arising from rural poverty and landlessness, which was blamed on British misrule.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Accordingly, the Palestinian revolt targeted the political and economic apparatus of the British colonial state, including the communications network, pipelines, police stations, army outposts and British personnel.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] It was this aspect of the revolt, rather than attacks on Jews or violence between rivals for leadership of the national movement, that most concerned the high commissioner.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The mandate authorities were further disturbed by the unity of purpose displayed during the six-month general strike and by the resurgence of pan-Arab nationalism as evidenced by the rise of the Istiqlal Party.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In response to these challenges the British army command ("I" Branch) and battalion headquarters across Palestine issued a daily intelligence bulletin every afternoon detailing political developments.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Special Service Officers (SSOs) assigned to intelligence gathering reported directly to their local command headquarters and their cars were equipped with wireless transmitters so that high grade intelligence could be reported directly to "I" Branch immediately.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] These sources of intelligence gradually became more important than those of the C.I.D. in Palestine, which had been dependent on Arab informers, and which were no longer reliable.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In September 1937, the Jewish Agency appointed Reuven Zaslany liaison officer for intelligence and security affairs between the Political Department of the Jewish Agency and the intelligence arms of the Royal Air Force and the C.I.D.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Zaslany sifted through intelligence collected by Jewish-controlled field operatives and forwarded it to the British military.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] He was a frequent visitor at the headquarters of British intelligence and the army, the police and C.I.D. and he also travelled to Damascus to liaise with the Arab opposition's peace bands and with the British Consul in Iraq.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Colonel Frederick Kisch, a British army officer and Zionist leader, was appointed chief liaison officer between the British army and the Jewish Agency Executive with Zaslany as his deputy.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In 1937 the Jewish Agency's intelligence groups were responsible for bugging the Peel Commission hearings in Palestine.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The *Haganah* (Hebrew for "defence"), a Jewish paramilitary organisation, actively supported British efforts to suppress the uprising, which reached 10,000 Arab fighters at their peak during the summer and fall of 1938.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Although the British administration did not officially recognise the *Haganah*, the British security forces cooperated with it by forming the Jewish Settlement Police, Jewish Supernumerary Police, and Special Night Squads.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The Special Night Squads engaged in activities described by colonial administrator Sir Hugh Foot, as 'extreme and cruel' involving torture, whipping, abuse and execution of Arabs.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Independently of the British, *Ta'as*, the Haganah's clandestine munitions industry, developed an 81-mm mortar and manufactured mines and grenades, 17,500 of the latter being produced for use during the revolt.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The administration also provided security services to Jewish commercial concerns at cost.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Jewish and British officials worked together to co-ordinate manhunts and collective actions against villages and also discussed the imposition of penalties and sentences.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The rebellion also inspired the Jewish Agency to expand the intelligence-gathering of its Political Department and especially of its Arab Division, with the focus changing from political to military intelligence.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The Arab Division set up a network of Jewish controllers and Arab agents around the country.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Some of the intelligence gathered was shared with the British administration, the exchange of information sometimes being conducted by Moshe Shertok, then head of the Jewish Agency, directly with the high commissioner himself.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Shertok also advised the administration on political affairs, on one occasion convincing the high commissioner not to arrest Professor Joseph Klausner, a Revisionist Maximalist activist who had played a key role in the riots of 1929, because of the likely negative consequences.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] There was no single body within the Jewish settlement capable of co-ordinating intelligence gathering before 1939.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Until then there were four separate organisations without any regular or formal liaison.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In mid-1939 the effort to co-ordinate the activities of these groups was led by Shaul Avigur and Moshe Shertok.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In 1931, a Revisionist underground splinter group broke off from Haganah, calling itself the *Irgun* organisation (or *Etzel*).
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The organisation took its orders from Revisionist leader Ze'ev Jabotinsky who was at odds with the dominant Labour Zionist movement led by David Ben-Gurion.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The rift between the two Zionist movements further deteriorated in 1933 when two Revisionists were blamed for the murder of Haim Arlosoroff, who had negotiated the Haavara Agreement between the Jewish Agency and Nazi Germany.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Ultimately, however, the events of the Arab Revolt blurred the differences between the gradualist approach of Ben-Gurion and the Maximalist Iron Wall approach of Jabotinsky and turned militarist patriotism into a bipartisan philosophy.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Indeed, Ben-Gurion's own Special Operations Squads conducted a punitive operation in the Arab village of Lubya firing weapons into a room through a window killing two men and one woman and injuring three people, including two children.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] From October 1937 the Irgun instituted a wave of bombings against Arab crowds and buses.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] For the first time in the conflict massive bombs were placed in crowded Arab public places, killing and maiming dozens.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] These attacks substantially increased Arab casualties and sowed terror among the population.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The first attack was on 11 November 1937, killing two Arabs at the bus depot near Jaffa Street in Jerusalem and then on 14 November, a day later commemorated as the "Day of the Breaking of the *Havlagah* (restraint)," Arabs were killed in simultaneous attacks around Palestine.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] More deadly attacks followed: on 6 July 1938 21 Arabs were killed and 52 wounded by a bomb in a Haifa market; on 25 July a second market bomb in Haifa killed at least 39 Arabs and injured 70; a bomb in Jaffa's vegetable market on 26 August killed 24 Arabs and wounded 39.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The attacks were condemned by the Jewish Agency.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The "peace bands" (*fasa'il al-salam*) or "Nashashibi units" were made up of disaffected Arab peasants recruited by the British administration and the Nashashibis in late 1938 to battle against Arab rebels during the revolt.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Despite their peasant origins the bands were representative mainly of the interests of landlords and rural notables.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Some peace bands also sprang up in the Nablus area, on Mount Carmel (a stronghold of the Druze who largely opposed the rebellion after 1937), and around Nazareth without connection to the Nashashibi-Husayni power struggle.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] From December 1937 the main opposition figures among the Arabs approached the Jewish Agency for funding and assistance, motivated by the assassination campaign pursued by the rebels at the behest of the Husseini leadership.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] From early in 1938 the Nashashibis received funding specifically to conduct anti-rebel operations, with Raghib al-Nashashibi himself receiving £5,000.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The British also supplied funding to the peace bands and sometimes directed their operations.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Fakhri Nashashibi was particularly successful in recruiting peace bands in the Hebron hills, on one occasion in December 1938 gathering 3,000 villagers for a rally in Yatta, also attended by the British military commander of the Jerusalem District General Richard O'Connor.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Just two months earlier, on 15 October 1938, rebels had seized the Old City and barricaded the gates.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] O'Connor had planned the operation by which men of the Coldstream Guards, Royal Northumberland Fusiliers and Black Watch recaptured the Old City, killing 19 rebels.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Towards the end of the revolt in May 1939 the authorities dissolved the peace bands and confiscated their arms.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] However, because members of the bands had become tainted in the eyes of the Palestinian Arabs, and some were under sentence of death, they had little choice but to continue the battle against the national movement's leadership, which they did with the continuing help of the Zionist movement.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] At least 282 rebel leaders took part in the Arab Revolt, including four Christians.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Rebel forces consisted of loosely organized bands known as *fasa'il* (sing: *fasil*).
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The leader of a *fasil* was known as a *qa'id al-fasil* (pl.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] *quwwa'id al-fasa'il*), which means "band commander".
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The Jewish press often referred to them as "brigands", while the British authorities and media called them "bandits", "terrorists", "rebels" or "insurgents", but never "nationalists".
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] *Ursabat* (meaning "gangs") was another Arabic term used for the rebels, and it spawned the British soldiers' nickname for all rebels, which was *Oozlebart*.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] According to historian Simon Anglim, the rebel groups were divided into general categories: *mujahadeen* and *fedayeen*.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The former were guerrillas who engaged in armed confrontations, while the latter committed acts of sabotage.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] According to later accounts of some surviving rebel leaders from the Galilee, the *mujahideen* maintained little coordination with the nominal hierarchy of the revolt.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Most ambushes were the result of a local initiative undertaken by a *qa'id* or a group of *quwwa'id* from the same area.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Abdul Khallik was an effective peasant leader appointed by Fawzi al-Qawuqji who caused great damage and loss of life in the Nazareth District and was thus a significant adversary of the Mandate and Jewish settlement authorities.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] He was trapped by British troops in a major engagement on 2 October 1938 and was killed whilst trying to lead his men to safety.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Abu Ibrahim al-Kabir was the main Qassamite rebel leader in the Upper Galilee and was the only active rebel leader on the ground who was a member of the Damascus-based Central Committee of National Jihad.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Abdallah al-Asbah was a prominent commander active in the Safad region of northeastern Galilee.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] He was killed by British forces who besieged him and his comrades near the border with Lebanon in early 1937.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Abd al-Rahim al-Hajj Muhammad from the Tulkarm area was a deeply religious, intellectual man and as a fervent anti-Zionist, he was deeply committed to the revolt.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] He was regarded second to Qawukji in terms of leadership ability and maintained his independence from the exiled rebel leadership in Damascus.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] He personally led his *fasa'il* and carried out nighttime attacks against British targets in the revolt's early stage in 1936.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] When the revolt was renewed in April 1937, he established a more organised command hierarchy consisting of four main brigades who operated in the north-central highlands (Tulkarm–Nablus–Jenin area).
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] He competed for the position of General Commander of the Revolt with Aref Abdul Razzik, and the two served the post in rotation from September 1938 to February 1939, when al-Hajj Muhammad was confirmed as the sole General Commander.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Yusuf Abu Durra, a Qassamite leader in the Jenin area, was born in Silat al-Harithiya and before becoming a rebel worked as a Gazoz vendor.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] He was said to be a narrow-minded man who thrived on extortion and cruelty and thus became greatly feared.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Yusuf Hamdan was Durra's more respected lieutenant and later a leader of his own unit; he was killed by an army patrol in 1939 and buried in al-Lajjun.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Durra himself was apprehended by the Arab Legion in Transjordan on 25 July 1939 and subsequently hanged.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Fakhri Abdul Hadi of Arrabah worked closely with Fawzi al-Qawukji in 1936, but later defected to the British authorities.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] He bargained for a pardon by offering to collaborate with the British on countering rebel propaganda.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Once on the payroll of the British consul in Damascus, Gilbert Mackereth, he carried out many attacks against the rebels in 1938–1939 as leader of his own "peace band".
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Aref Abdul Razzik of Tayibe was responsible for the area south of Tulkarm and was known for evading capture whilst being pursued by the security forces.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] He signed his bulletins as 'The Ghost of Sheikh Qassam'.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Razzik assumed a place in British army folklore and the troops sang a song about him.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Razzik was capable and daring and gained a reputation as one of the army's problem heroes.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Issa Battat was a peasant leader in the southern hills below Jerusalem who caused enormous damage to security patrols in his area.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] He was killed by a patrol of armed police in a battle near Hebron in 1937.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In the first phase of the revolt, around 300 volunteers, mostly veterans of the Ottoman Army and/or rebels from the Great Syrian Revolt (1925–1927), deployed in northern Palestine.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Their overall commander was Fawzi al-Qawuqji and his deputies were Said al-As and Muhammad al-Ashmar.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Qawuqji also led the volunteer force's Iraqi and Transjordanian battalions, and al-Ashmar was commander of the Syrian battalion, which largely consisted of volunteers from Damascus's al-Midan Quarter, Hama and Homs.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The Druze ex-Ottoman officer, Hamad Sa'ab, commanded the Lebanese battalion.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In the contest of wills between the British Empire and Palestinian aspirants for statehood, the respective efforts to secure the financial means to sustain the hostilities also played out as a battle for funding.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The Mandatory Authority's repression of the revolt was bankrolled directly from London and through the revenue stream supplied to the administration by land and property taxes, stamp duties, excises on manufactured goods and customs duties on imports and exports.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Draconian collective punishment fines on the peasantry –many heavily burdened already by debt and unable to pay them – were such that revenue extracted from punitive fines exceeded, and more than compensated for, the revenue lost during the revolt.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The majority of funds raised to finance the uprising came from Arab/Muslim sources.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In the broader Arab/Muslim world a measure of financial aid, never vast, filtered in from Egypt, Syria, Iraq and Muslim India for some time.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In Palestine, the peasantry, often debt-ridden, could offer little towards subsidising the resistance.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The AHC's functions in this capacity were truncated when it was abolished by the British authorities in October 1937.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Displaced in Damascus, its leaders were cut off from contact with field units and donations gradually dried up. al-Husayni, by then in exile, proved unable to raise money, and in Syria militant contacts were informed by July 1938 that they would have to make do on their own.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] By 1938 the drop in revenues caused militant gangs to resort to extortion and robbery, often draining villages of ready cash reserves set aside to pay government fines, which then had to be met by the sale of crops and livestock.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Some contributions were obtained from American sources.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] A great deal of speculation later arose around the purported role of Germany and Italy in backing the revolt financially, based on early claims by Jewish operatives that both countries were fomenting the uprising by funneling cash and weapons to the insurgents.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] German plans to ship arms to the rebels were never implemented due to distrust of the Saudi middlemen.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Italian attempts to furnish arms by the same venue were thwarted by British intelligence.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The British never found arms or munitions of German or Italian provenance.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The rebels utilized the Italian funding to smuggle weapons into Palestine via Syria.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Total Italian funding amounted to approximately £150.000.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] It stopped in late 1938 and played no decisive role since the uprising peaked after that date.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In the first years after 1933 Germany was approached by a variety of Arab nationalist groups from Palestine and abroad asking for aid, but Germany categorically refused.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Maintaining good relations with the British was still considered to be of the uppermost priority, hence it limited itself to expressing its sympathy and moral support.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Soon after the outbreak of the revolt, in December 1936, Germany was approached by the rebel commander Fawzi al-Qawuqji and in January 1937 by representatives of the Arab Higher Committee, both requesting arms and money, but again in vain.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In July al-Husayni himself approached Walter Döhle, new German general consul in Jerusalem, to request support for the "battle against the Jews".
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Döhle found that Germany's hesitation in supporting the rebels had caused pro-German sentiment among Palestinian Arabs to waver.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Some limited German funding for the revolt can be dated to around the summer of 1938 and was perhaps related to a goal of distracting the British from the on-going occupation of Czechoslovakia.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The Abwehr gave money to al-Husayni and other sums were funneled via Saudi Arabia.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Despite the intervention of up to 50,000 British troops and 15,000 Haganah men, the uprising continued for over three years.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] By the time it concluded in September 1939, more than 5,000 Arabs, over 300 Jews, and 262 Britons had been killed and at least 15,000 Arabs were wounded.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In the overall context of the Jewish settlement's development in the 1930s the physical losses endured during the revolt were relatively insignificant.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Although hundreds were killed and property was damaged no Jewish settlement was captured or destroyed and several dozen new ones were established.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Over 50,000 new Jewish immigrants arrived in Palestine.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In 1936 Jews made up about one-third of the population.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The hostilities contributed to further disengagement of the Jewish and Arab economies in Palestine, which were intertwined to some extent until that time.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Development of the economy and infrastructure accelerated.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The settlement's transportation capabilities were enhanced and Jewish unemployment was relieved owing to the employment of police officers, and replacement of striking Arab labourers, employees, craftsman and farmers by Jewish workers.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Most of the important industries in Palestine were owned by Jews and in trade and the banking sector they were much better placed than the Arabs.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] As a result of collaboration with the British colonial authorities and security forces many thousands of young men had their first experience of military training, which Moshe Shertok and Haganah leader Eliyahu Golomb cited as one of the fruits of the Haganah's policy of havlagah (restraint).
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Britain published the White Paper of 1939, a policy paper that restricted Jewish immigration and land acquisition.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Although the Jewish settlement in Palestine was dismayed by the white paper, David Ben-Gurion remained undeterred, believing that the policy would not be implemented, and in fact Neville Chamberlain had told him that the policy would last at the very most only for the duration of the war.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In the event the White Paper quotas were exhausted only in December 1944, over five and a half years later, and in the same period the United Kingdom absorbed 50,000 Jewish refugees and the British Commonwealth (Australia, Canada and South Africa) took many thousands more.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] During the War over 30,000 Jews joined the British forces and even the Irgun ceased operations against the British until 1944.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The revolt weakened the military strength of Palestinian Arabs in advance of their ultimate confrontation with the Jewish settlement in the 1947–48 Civil War in Mandatory Palestine and was, according to Benny Morris, thus counterproductive.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] During the uprising, British authorities attempted to confiscate all weapons from the Arab population.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] This, and the destruction of the main Arab political leadership in the revolt, greatly hindered their military efforts in the 1948 Palestine war, where imbalances between the Jewish and Arab economic performance, social cohesion, political organisation and military capability became apparent.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The Mufti, Hajj Amin al-Husseini and his supporters directed a Jihad against any person who did not obey the Mufti.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Their national struggle was a religious holy war, and the incarnation of both the Palestinian Arab nation and Islam was Hajj Amin al-Husseini.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Anyone who rejected his leadership was a heretic and his life was forfeit.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] After the Peel report publication, the murders of Arabs leaders who opposed the Mufti were accelerated.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Pressed by the assassination campaign pursued by the rebels at the behest of the Husseini leadership, the opposition had a security cooperation with the Jews.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The flight of wealthy Arabs, which occurred during the revolt, was also replicated in 1947–49.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Thousands of Palestinian houses were destroyed, and massive financial costs were incurred because of the general strike and the devastation of fields, crops and orchards.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The economic boycott further damaged the fragile Palestinian Arab economy through loss of sales and goods and increased unemployment.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The new policy was regarded by many as incompatible with the commitment to a Jewish National Home in Palestine, as proclaimed in the 1917 Balfour Declaration.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Al-Husseini rejected it, although it seems that this reaction was the reverse of that of the ordinary Palestinian Arab.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] His biographer, Philip Mattar wrote that in that case, the Mufti preferred his personal interests and the ideology rather than the practical considerations.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In February 1939 Secretary of State for Dominion Affairs Malcolm MacDonald called together a conference of Arab and Zionist leaders on the future of Palestine at St.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] James's Palace in London but the discussions ended without agreement on 27 March.The government's new policy as published in White Paper of 17 May had been determined already and despite Jewish protests and Irgun attacks the British remained resolute.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] There was a growing feeling among British officials that there was nothing left for them to do in Palestine.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Perhaps the ultimate achievement of the Arab Revolt was to make the British sick of Palestine.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Major-General Bernard "Monty" Montgomery concluded, "the Jew murders the Arab and the Arab murders the Jew.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] This is what is going on in Palestine now.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p03] In 2003, Ted Swedenburg argued that 1936–1939 Arab Revolt has been and still is marginalized in both Western and Israeli historiography on Palestine, and even progressive Western scholars have little to say about the anti-colonial struggle of the Palestinian Arab rebels against the British Empire.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p03] According to Swedenburg's analysis, for instance, the Zionist version of Israeli history acknowledges only one authentic national movement: the struggle for Jewish self-determination that resulted in the Israeli Declaration of Independence in May 1948.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p03] Swedenburg writes that the Zionist narrative has no room for an anticolonial and anti-British Palestinian national revolt.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p03] Zionists often describe the revolt as a series of "events" (Hebrew מאורעות תרצ"ו-תרצ"ט) "riots", or "happenings".
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p03] The appropriate description was debated by Jewish Agency officials, who were keen not to give a negative impression of Palestine to prospective immigrants In private, however, David Ben-Gurion was unequivocal: the Arabs, he said, were "fighting dispossession ...
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p03] He concludes that it was the "Palestine surge"—that is, London's use of sheer weight of numbers to overwhelm and crush the Arab rebels—was a success.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p03] Matthew Hughes, a leading authority on the Revolt, notes that it is a standard move in British historiography to contrast the relative mildness of British counter-insurgency achievements with those of other Western colonial powers.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p03] A contrast is frequently drawn between the German suppression of the Herero, Belgium's genocide in the Congo and France's violence in Algeria to the winning-the-hearts-and-minds approach Britain is said to have adopted in Kenya in containing the Mau Mau revolt.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p03] One British military commander asserted that "If the Germans were in occupation in Haifa we'd not have any bloody troubles from the Arabs." Nonetheless, while moderating forces did mitigate the violence, atrocities were committed, torture used, brutality commonplace.
[src:crimean-war/1936-1939-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p03] Collective punishment, the razing of villages, the smashing of personal property in homes, and the destruction of foodstocks was widespread.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] In August 1991, hardliners of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union (CPSU) attempted to forcibly seize control of the country from Mikhail Gorbachev, who was Soviet president and General Secretary of the CPSU at the time.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The coup leaders consisted of top military and civilian officials, including Vice President Gennady Yanayev, who together formed the State Committee on the State of Emergency (Russian: ГКЧП, romanized: *GKChP*).
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Opposed to Gorbachev's reform program, they were angry at the loss of control over Eastern European states and fearful of the New Union Treaty, which was on the verge of being signed by the Soviet Union (USSR).
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The treaty was to decentralize much of the central Soviet government's power and distribute it among its fifteen republics.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Boris Yeltsin's demand for more autonomy to the republics opened a window for the plotters to organize the coup.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The attempt took place between 19 and 21 August 1991; as a result, the events were referred to as the **August Coup**.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The GKChP hardliners dispatched KGB agents who detained Gorbachev at his dacha but failed to detain the recently elected president of Russia, Boris Yeltsin, who had been both an ally and critic of Gorbachev.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The GKChP was poorly organized and met with effective resistance by both Yeltsin and a civilian campaign of anti-authoritarian protesters, mainly in Moscow.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The coup collapsed in two days, and Gorbachev returned to office while the plotters all lost their posts.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Yeltsin subsequently became the dominant leader and Gorbachev lost much of his influence.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The failed coup led to both the immediate collapse of the CPSU and the dissolution of the USSR four months later.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Following the capitulation of the GKChP, popularly referred to as the "Gang of Eight", both the Supreme Court of the Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic (RSFSR) and President Gorbachev described its actions as a coup attempt.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Since assuming power as General Secretary of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union in 1985, Gorbachev had embarked on an ambitious reform program embodied in the twin concepts of *perestroika* (economic and political restructuring) and *glasnost* (openness).
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] These moves prompted resistance and suspicion on the part of hard-line members of the *nomenklatura*.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The reforms also caused nationalist agitation on the part of the Soviet Union's non-Russian minorities to grow, and there were fears that some or all of the union republics might secede.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] In 1991, the Soviet Union was in a severe economic and political crisis.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] In 1990, Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania and Armenia had already declared the restoration of their independence from the Soviet Union.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] In January 1991, a violent attempt to return Lithuania to the Soviet Union by force took place.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] About a week later, a similar attempt was engineered by local pro-Soviet forces to overthrow Latvian authorities.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] These attempts failed, and Lithuania and Latvia retained their statehood.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Russia declared its sovereignty on 12 June 1990 and thereafter limited the application of Soviet laws, in particular those governing finance and the economy, on Russian territory.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The Supreme Soviet of the Russian SFSR adopted laws that contradicted Soviet laws (the so-called War of Laws).
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] In the unionwide referendum on 17 March 1991, boycotted by the Baltic states, Armenia, Georgia, and Moldova, a supermajority of residents in the other republics expressed the desire to retain the renewed Soviet Union, with 77.85% voting in favor.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Following negotiations, eight of the remaining nine republics (Ukraine abstaining) approved the New Union Treaty with some conditions.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The treaty was to make the Soviet Union a federation of independent republics called the Union of Soviet Sovereign Republics, with a common president, foreign policy, and military.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Russia, Kazakhstan and Uzbekistan were to sign the Treaty in Moscow on 20 August 1991.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The KGB began considering a coup in September 1990.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Soviet politician Alexander Yakovlev began warning Gorbachev about the possibility of one after the 28th Party Congress in June 1990.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] On 11 December 1990, KGB Chairman Vladimir Kryuchkov made a "call for order" over the Moscow Programme television station.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] That day, he asked two KGB officers to prepare measures to be taken in the event a state of emergency was declared in the USSR.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] When Kryuchkov complained about the Soviet Union's growing instability to the Congress of People's Deputies, Gorbachev attempted to appease him by issuing a presidential decree enhancing the powers of the KGB and appointing Pugo to the Cabinet as Minister of Internal Affairs.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Foreign Secretary Eduard Shevardnadze resigned in protest and rejected an offered appointment as vice president, warning that "a dictatorship is coming." Gorbachev was forced to appoint Yanayev in his place.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Beginning with the January Events in Lithuania, members of Gorbachev's Cabinet hoped that he could be persuaded to declare a state of emergency and "restore order," and formed the State Committee on the State of Emergency (GKChP).
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] On 17 June 1991, Soviet premier Pavlov requested extraordinary powers from the Supreme Soviet.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Several days later, Moscow Mayor Gavriil Popov informed U.S. ambassador to the Soviet Union Jack F.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Matlock Jr. that a coup against Gorbachev was being planned.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] When Matlock tried to warn him, Gorbachev falsely assumed that his own Cabinet was not involved and underestimated the risk of a coup.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Gorbachev reversed Pavlov's request for more powers and jokingly told his Cabinet "The coup is over," remaining oblivious to their plans.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] On 23 July 1991, several party functionaries and literati published a piece in the hardline *Sovetskaya Rossiya* newspaper, entitled "A Word to the People", that called for decisive action to prevent calamity.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Six days later, on 29 July, Gorbachev, Russian president Boris Yeltsin and Kazakh president Nursultan Nazarbayev discussed the possibility of replacing hardliners such as Pavlov, Yazov, Kryuchkov and Pugo with more liberal figures, with Nazarbayev as Prime Minister (in Pavlov's place).
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Kryuchkov, who had placed Gorbachev under close surveillance as Subject 110 several months earlier, eventually got wind of the conversation from an electronic bug planted by Gorbachev's bodyguard, Vladimir Medvedev.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Yeltsin also prepared for a coup by establishing a secret defense committee, ordering military and KGB commands to side with RSFSR authorities and establishing a "reserve government" about 70 kilometers from Sverdlovsk under Deputy Prime Minister Oleg Lobov.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] On 4 August, Gorbachev went on holiday to his dacha in Foros, Crimea.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] He planned to return to Moscow in time for the New Union Treaty signing on 20 August.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] On 15 August, the text of the draft treaty was published, which would have stripped the coup planners of much of their authority.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] On 17 August, the members of the GKChP met at a KGB guesthouse in Moscow and studied the treaty document.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Decisions were made to introduce a state of emergency from 19 August, to form a State Emergency Committee, and require Gorbachev to sign the relevant decrees or to resign and transfer powers to Vice President Yanayev.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] They believed the pact would pave the way for the Soviet Union's breakup, and decided it was time to act.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The next day, Baklanov, Boldin, Shenin, and Soviet Deputy Defense Minister General Valentin Varennikov flew to Crimea for a meeting with Gorbachev.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Yazov ordered General Pavel Grachev, commander of the Soviet Airborne Forces, to begin coordinating with KGB Deputy Chairmen Viktor Grushko and Genii Ageev to implement martial law.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] At 4:32 pm on 18 August, the GKChP cut communications to Gorbachev's dacha, including telephone landlines and the nuclear command and control system.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Eight minutes later Lieutenant General Yuri Plekhanov, Head of the Ninth Chief Directorate of the KGB, allowed the group into Gorbachev's dacha.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Gorbachev realized what was happening after discovering the telephone outages.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Baklanov, Boldin, Shenin and Varennikov demanded that Gorbachev either declare a state of emergency or resign and name Yanayev as acting president to allow the members of the GKChP "to restore order" to the country.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Gorbachev has always claimed that he refused point-blank to accept the ultimatum.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Varennikov has insisted that Gorbachev said: "Damn you.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] But report my opinion!" However, those present at the dacha at the time testified that Baklanov, Boldin, Shenin and Varennikov had been clearly disappointed and nervous after the meeting with Gorbachev.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Gorbachev is said to have insulted Varennikov by pretending to forget his name, and to have told his former trusted advisor Boldin "Shut up, you prick!
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] How dare you give me lectures about the situation in the country!" With Gorbachev's refusal, the conspirators ordered that he remain confined to the dacha.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Additional KGB security guards were placed at the dacha gates with orders to stop anybody from leaving.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] At 7:30 pm, Baklanov, Boldin, Shenin and Varennikov flew to Moscow, accompanied by Plekhanov.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] His deputy, Vyacheslav Generalov, remained "on the farm" in Foros.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] At 8:00 pm, Yanayev, Pavlov, Kryuchkov, Yazov, Pugo and Soviet Supreme Soviet Chairman Anatoly Lukyanov gathered in the Kremlin cabinet of the Prime Minister, discussing and editing the documents of the State Emergency Committee.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] At 10:15 pm, they were joined by Baklanov, Shenin, Boldin, Varennikov and Plekhanov.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] It was decided to publicly declare Gorbachev ill.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Yanayev hesitated, but the others convinced him that leadership and responsibility would be collective.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] At 11:25 pm, Yanayev signed a decree entrusting himself with presidential powers.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] GKChP members ordered that 250,000 pairs of handcuffs from a factory in Pskov be sent to Moscow, also ordering 300,000 arrest forms.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Kryuchkov doubled the pay of all KGB personnel, called them back from holiday, and placed them on alert.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Lefortovo Prison was emptied to receive prisoners.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The members of the GKChP met in the Kremlin after Baklanov, Boldin, Shenin and Varennikov returned from Crimea.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Yanayev signed the decree naming himself acting Soviet President, using the pretense of Gorbachev's inability to perform presidential duties due to "illness".
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] However, Russian investigators later identified Kryuchkov as the key planner of the coup.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Yanayev later claimed that he had been forced to participate in the coup under the threat of arrest.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The eight aforementioned GKChP members became known as the "Gang of Eight".
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The GKChP banned all Moscow newspapers except for nine party-controlled newspapers.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] At 1:00 am, Yanayev signed documents on the formation of the State Committee for the State of Emergency (GKChP), consisting of himself, Pavlov, Kryuchkov, Yazov, Pugo, Baklanov, Tizyakov and Starodubtsev.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Included in the documents was the "Appeal to the Soviet people".
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The GKChP members present signed GKChP Resolution No.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] At 4:00 am, the Sevastopol regiment of KGB border troops surrounded Gorbachev's presidential dacha in Foros.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] By order of Soviet Air Defense Chief of Staff Colonel-General Igor Maltsev, two tractors blocked the runway on which the President's aircraft were located: a Tu-134 jet and Mi-8 helicopter.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Starting at 6:00 am, all of the GKChP documents were broadcast over state radio and television.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The KGB immediately issued an arrest list that included newly elected Russian SFSR president Boris Yeltsin, his allies, and the leaders of the umbrella activist group Democratic Russia.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The Russian SFSR-controlled Radio Rossii and Televidenie Rossii, plus Ekho Moskvy, the only independent political radio station, were taken off the air.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] However, the latter station later resumed its broadcasts and became a source of reliable information during the coup.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The BBC World Service and Voice of America were also able to provide continuous coverage.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Gorbachev and his family heard the news from a BBC bulletin on a small Sony transistor radio that had not been seized.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] For the next several days, he refused to take food from outside the dacha to avoid being poisoned, and took long outdoor strolls to refute reports of his ill health.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Under Yanayev's orders, units of the Tamanskaya mechanized infantry and Kantemirovskaya armored division rolled into Moscow, along with airborne troops.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Around 4,000 soldiers, 350 tanks, 300 armoured personnel carriers and 420 trucks were sent to Moscow.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Four Russian SFSR people's deputies were detained by the KGB at a Soviet Army base near the capital.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] However, almost no other arrests were made by the KGB during the coup.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Ulysse Gosset and Vladimir Federovski later alleged that the KGB was planning to carry out a much larger wave of arrests two weeks after the coup, after which it would have abolished almost all legislative and local administrative structures under a highly centralized Council of Ministers.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Yanayev instructed Foreign Minister Alexander Bessmertnykh to make a statement requesting formal diplomatic recognition from foreign governments and the United Nations.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The GKChP conspirators considered detaining Yeltsin upon his return from a visit to Kazakhstan on 17 August but failed when Yeltsin redirected his flight from Chkalovsky Air Base northeast of Moscow to Vnukovo Airport southwest of the city.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Afterwards, they considered capturing him at his dacha near Moscow.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The KGB Alpha Group surrounded his dacha with Spetsnaz, but for undisclosed reasons did not apprehend him.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The commanding officer, Viktor Karpukhin, later alleged that he had received an order from Kryuchkov to arrest Yeltsin but disobeyed it, although his account has been questioned.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The failure to arrest Yeltsin proved fatal to the plotters' plans.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Yeltsin initially wanted to remain at the dacha and organize a rival government, but Kobets advised his group to travel to the White House, Russia's parliament building, to maintain communications with coup opponents.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] They arrived and occupied the building at 9:00 am.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Together with Silayev and Khasbulatov, Yeltsin issued a declaration "To the Citizens of Russia" that condemned the GKChP's actions as a reactionary anti-constitutional coup.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The military was urged not to take part in the coup, and local authorities were asked to follow laws from the RSFSR president rather than the GKChP.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Although he initially avoided the measure to avoid sparking a civil war, Yeltsin also subsequently took command of all Soviet military and security forces in the RSFSR.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The joint declaration called for a general strike, with the demand to let Gorbachev address the people.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] This declaration was distributed around Moscow in the form of flyers, and disseminated nationwide through medium-wave radio and Usenet newsgroups via the RELCOM computer network.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] *Izvestia* newspaper workers threatened to go on strike unless Yeltsin's proclamation was printed in the paper.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The GKChP relied on regional and local soviets, mostly still dominated by the Communist Party, to support the coup by forming emergency committees to repress dissidence.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The CPSU Secretariat under Boldin sent coded telegrams to local party committees to assist the coup.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Yeltsin's authorities later discovered that nearly 70 percent of the committees either backed it or attempted to remain neutral.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Within the RSFSR, the oblasts of Samara, Lipetsk, Tambov, Saratov, Orenburg, Irkutsk, and Tomsk and the krai of Altai and Krasnodar all supported the coup and pressured *raikom* to do so as well, while only three oblasts aside from Moscow and Leningrad opposed it.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] However, some of the soviets faced internal resistance against emergency rule.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republics of Tatarstan, Checheno-Ingushetia, and Abkhazia all sided with the GKChP.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Soviet Armed Forces officers seized control of city halls and government buildings around the country claiming to be in control, as well as television stations in the Baltic states.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The Soviet public was divided on the coup.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] A poll in the RSFSR by Mnenie on the morning of 19 August showed that 23.6 percent of Russians believed the GKChP could improve living standards, while 41.9 percent had no opinion.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] However, separate polls by Interfax showed that many Russians, including 71 percent of Leningrad residents, feared the return of mass repression.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The GKChP enjoyed strong support in the Russian-majority regions of Estonia and Transnistria, while Yeltsin enjoyed strong support in Sverdlovsk and Nizhny Novgorod.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] At 10:00 am, Rutskoy, Silayev, and Khasbulatov delivered a letter to Lukyanov demanding a medical exam of Gorbachev by the World Health Organization and a meeting between themselves, Yeltsin, Gorbachev, and Yanayev within 24 hours.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Rutskoy later visited Patriarch Alexy II of Moscow, spiritual leader of the Russian Orthodox Church, and convinced him to declare support for Yeltsin.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Meanwhile, in Leningrad, Military District Commander Viktor Samsonov ordered the formation of an emergency committee for the city, chaired by Leningrad First Secretary Boris Gidaspov, to circumvent Sobchak's democratically elected municipal government.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Samsonov's troops were ultimately blocked by hundreds of thousands of demonstrators supported by the police, which forced Leningrad Television to broadcast a statement by Sobchak.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Workers at the Kirov Plant went on strike in support of Yeltsin.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Moscow First Secretary Yuri Prokofev attempted a similar maneuver in the capital but was rebuffed when Boris Nikolskii refused to accept the office of Mayor of Moscow.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] At 11:00 am, RSFSR Foreign Minister Andrei Kozyrev held a press conference for foreign journalists and diplomats, and gained the support of most of the West for Yeltsin.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] That afternoon, Moscow citizens began gathering around the White House, erecting barricades around it.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] In response, Yanayev declared a state of emergency in Moscow at 4:00 pm.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] He declared at a 5:00 pm press conference that Gorbachev was "resting".
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] He said: "Over these years he has got very tired and needs some time to get his health back." Yanayev's shaking hands led some people to think he was drunk, and his trembling voice and weak posture made his words unconvincing.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Gorbachev's security detail managed to construct a makeshift television antenna so he and his family could watch the press conference.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] After viewing the conference, Gorbachev expressed confidence that Yeltsin would be able to stop the coup.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] That night, his family smuggled out a videotape of Gorbachev condemning the coup.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Yanayev and the rest of the State Committee ordered the Cabinet of Ministers to alter the five-year plan of the time to relieve the housing shortage.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] All city dwellers were each given 1,000 square metres (1⁄3 acre) to combat winter shortages by growing fruits and vegetables.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Due to the illness of Valentin Pavlov, the duties of the Soviet head of the government were entrusted to First Deputy Prime Minister Vitaly Doguzhiyev.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Meanwhile, the Soviet forces carrying out the coup began to suffer from mass defections to the RSFSR as well as soldiers refusing to obey orders to shoot civilians.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Yeltsin asked his followers not to harass the soldiers and offered amnesty for any military servicemen who defected to oppose the coup.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Major Evdokimov, chief of staff of a tank battalion of the Tamanskaya Division guarding the White House, declared his loyalty to the leadership of the Russian SFSR.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Yeltsin climbed one of the tanks and addressed the crowd.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Unexpectedly, this episode was included in the state media's evening news.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Soviet Armed Forces officers loyal to the GKChP tried to prevent defections by confining soldiers to their barracks, but this only limited the availability of forces to carry out the coup.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] At 8:00 am, the Soviet General Staff ordered that the Cheget briefcase controlling Soviet nuclear weapons be returned to Moscow.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Although Gorbachev discovered that the GKChP's actions had cut off communications with the nuclear duty officers, the Cheget was returned to the capital by 2:00 pm.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] However, Soviet Air Force Commander-in-Chief Yevgeny Shaposhnikov opposed the coup and claimed in his memoirs that he and the commanders of the Soviet Navy and the Strategic Rocket Forces told Yazov that they would not follow orders for a nuclear launch.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] After the coup, Gorbachev refused to admit that he had lost control of the country's nuclear weapons.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] At noon, Moscow military district commander General Nikolai Kalinin, whom Yanayev appointed military commandant of Moscow, declared a curfew in Moscow from 11:00 pm to 5:00 am, effective 20 August.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] This was understood as a sign that an attack on the White House was imminent.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The defenders of the White House prepared themselves, most being unarmed.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Evdokimov's tanks were moved from the White House in the evening.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The makeshift White House defense headquarters was headed by General Konstantin Kobets, a Russian SFSR people's deputy.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Outside, Eduard Shevardnadze, Mstislav Rostropovich, and Yelena Bonner delivered speeches in support of Yeltsin.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] In the afternoon, Kryuchkov, Yazov and Pugo finally decided to attack the White House.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] This decision was supported by other GKChP members (with the exception of Pavlov, who had been sent to his dacha due to drunkenness).
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Alpha Group commander General Viktor Karpukhin and other senior unit officers, together with Airborne deputy commander Gen.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Alexander Lebed mingled with the crowds near the White House and assessed the possibility of such an operation.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Afterwards, Karpukhin and Vympel commander Colonel Boris Beskov tried to convince Ageyev that the operation would result in bloodshed and should be cancelled.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Lebed, with the consent of his superior Pavel Grachev, returned to the White House and secretly informed the defense headquarters that the attack would begin at 2:00 am the following morning.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] While the events were unfolding in the capital, Estonia's Supreme Council declared at 11:03 pm the full reinstatement of the independent status of the Republic of Estonia after 51 years.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] State-controlled TASS dispatches from 20 August emphasize a hardline approach against crime, especially economic crimes and the Russian mafia, which the GKChP blamed on increasing trade with the West.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Draft decrees were later discovered which would have allowed military and police patrols to shoot "hooligans," including pro-democracy demonstrators.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Three men were killed in the ensuing clash: Dmitry Komar, Vladimir Usov, and Ilya Krichevsky; several others were wounded.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Komar, a 22-year-old Soviet-Afghan War veteran, was shot and crushed trying to cover a moving IFV's observation slit.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Usov, a 37-year-old economist, was killed by a stray bullet while coming to Komar's aid.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The crowd set fire to an IFV and Krichevsky, a 28-year-old architect, was shot dead as the troops pulled back.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The three men were posthumously awarded the title Hero of the Soviet Union.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Reports also surfaced that Gorbachev had been placed under house arrest in Crimea.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] During the final day of her family's exile, Raisa Gorbacheva suffered a minor stroke.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] At 8:00 am, the troops began to leave Moscow.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Between 8:00 and 9:00 am, the GKChP members met in the Defence Ministry and, not knowing what to do, decided to send Kryuchkov, Yazov, Baklanov, Tizyakov, Anatoly Lukyanov, and Deputy CPSU General Secretary Vladimir Ivashko to Crimea to meet Gorbachev, who refused to meet them when they arrived.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] At 10:00 am, the session of the Supreme Soviet of the RSFSR opened in the White House, at which President Yeltsin spoke.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] At 1:00 pm, the Soviet Cabinet of Ministers circulated a statement about its non-involvement in the putsch.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] At 1:20 pm, Kryuchkov, Yazov, Baklanov, Tizyakov, Lukyanov and CPSU Central Committee Deputy General Secretary Vladimir Ivashko left for the airport, getting stuck in a traffic jam created by the Taman Division armored vehicles returning to their base.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] At 2:00 pm, the CPSU Central Committee Secretariat issued a statement demanding that the GKChP clarify the fate of the head of the Communist Party, Mikhail Gorbachev.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] At 4:08 pm, the plane with the GKChP delegation landed in Crimea.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] At 4:52 pm, a group of Russian deputies and public figures led by RSFSR Vice President Alexander Rutskoy, as well as Soviet Security Council members Yevgeny Primakov and Vadim Bakatin, flew to Gorbachev's dacha in Foros.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] They were accompanied by 36 officers of the RSFSR Ministry of Internal Affairs armed with machine guns, under the command of RSFSR Deputy Minister of Internal Affairs Andrei Dunaev.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Eight minutes later, at 5:00 pm, the GKChP delegation arrived at the presidential dacha.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] President Gorbachev refused to receive it and demanded that communication to the outside world be restored.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] At the same time, Yanayev signed a decree dissolving the State Emergency Committee and declaring all of its decisions invalid.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] At 7:16 pm, the plane of the Russian delegation led by Rutskoy landed in Crimea.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] At 8:00 pm, the Soviet General Prosecutor's Office initiated a criminal case into the attempted coup.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] At 8:10 pm, Rutskoy and his delegation went to see Gorbachev.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] According to eyewitnesses, the meeting was cordial and joyful, allowing them to momentarily forget divisions between Soviet and Russian authorities.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] From 9:40 to 10:10 pm, Gorbachev received Lukyanov and Ivashko in the presence of Rutskoy and Primakov, accusing the USSR Supreme Soviet Speaker of treason, and the party deputy of inaction during the putsch.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Around 10:00 pm, RSFSR Prosecutor General Valentin Stepankov signed an arrest warrant for the Emergency Committee members.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] That day, the Supreme Council of the Republic of Latvia declared its sovereignty officially completed with a law passed by its deputies, confirming the independence restoration act of 4 May as an official act.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] In Estonia, just a day after the restitution of the country's full independence, the Tallinn TV Tower was taken over by Soviet Russian airborne troops.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] But while television broadcasts were cut for a time, the radio signal was kept on the air after a handful of Estonian Defence League (the unified paramilitary forces of Estonia) members barricaded themselves in the tower's broadcasting studio.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] That evening, as news from Moscow about the coup's failure reached Tallinn, the Russian paratroopers left the TV tower and the Estonian capital.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] At one minute past midnight, Gorbachev, his family and assistants flew to Moscow on Rutskoy's plane.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The GKChP members were sent back on a different plane; only Kryuchkov flew in the presidential plane, under police custody (according to Rutskoy, "they [would] definitely not be shot down with him on board").
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Upon arrival, Kryuchkov, Yazov and Tizyakov were arrested on the airfield, which was illegal under Soviet law as officials representing the central government could only be arrested and tried under Soviet law, which prevailed over the laws of the constituent republics.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] At 2:00 am, when Gorbachev arrived at Moscow's Vnukovo Airport, television showed live footage of him walking down the airstairs wearing a knitted sweater.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Later, he would be criticized for not going to the White House, but to rest at his dacha.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] At 6:00 am, Soviet Vice President Yanayev was arrested in his office.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Boris Pugo and his wife died by suicide after being contacted by the RSFSR for a meeting over his role in the coup attempt.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Pavlov, Starodubtsev, Baklanov, Boldin, and Shenin would all be taken into custody within the next 48 hours.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Since several heads of the regional executive committees supported the GKChP, on 21 August 1991 the Supreme Soviet of the Russian SFSR adopted Decision No.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] 1626-1, which authorized Russian president Boris Yeltsin to appoint heads of regional administrations, although the Constitution of the Russian SFSR did not empower the president with such authority.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The Russian Supreme Soviet passed another decision the following day declaring the old imperial colors Russia's national flag; it replaced the Russian SFSR flag two months later.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Gorbachev posthumously awarded them with the title of Hero of the Soviet Union.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Yeltsin asked their relatives to forgive him for not being able to prevent their deaths.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Gorbachev initially tried to defend the CPSU, proclaiming at a 22 August press conference that it still represented a "progressive force" despite its leaders' participation in the coup.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Gorbachev resigned as CPSU general secretary on 24 August.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Vladimir Ivashko replaced him as acting General Secretary, but resigned on 29 August when the Supreme Soviet of the USSR suspended the activities of the party throughout the Soviet Union.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] In a decree, Yeltsin ordered the transfer of the CPSU archives to the state archive authorities, and nationalized all CPSU assets in the Russian SFSR (these included not only party committee headquarters but also assets such as educational institutions and hotels).
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The party's Central Committee headquarters were handed over to the Government of Moscow.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] On 6 November, Yeltsin issued a decree banning the party in Russia.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Estonia had declared re-independence on 20 August, Latvia the following day, while Lithuania had already done so on 11 March the previous year.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] On 24 August 1991, Mikhail Gorbachev created the so-called "Committee for the Operational Management of the Soviet Economy" (Комитет по оперативному управлению народным хозяйством СССР), to replace the USSR Cabinet of Ministers headed by Valentin Pavlov, a GKChP member.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Russian prime minister Ivan Silayev headed the committee.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] That same day, Ukraine's Verkhovna Rada adopted the Act of Independence of Ukraine and called for a referendum on support of the Act of Independence.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] On 25 August, the Supreme Soviet of the Byelorussian SSR announced its Declaration of Sovereignty as a constitutional law.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] On 28 August, the Supreme Soviet of the USSR dismissed Prime Minister Pavlov and entrusted the functions of the Soviet government to the Committee for the Operational Management of the Soviet Economy.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The next day, Supreme Soviet Chairman Anatoly Lukyanov was arrested.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] On 27 August, the Supreme Soviet of Moldova declared the independence of Moldova from the Soviet Union.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The Supreme Soviets of Azerbaijan and Kyrgyzstan did the same on 30 and 31 August, respectively.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] On 5 September, the Congress of People's Deputies of the Soviet Union adopted Soviet Law No.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] 2392-1 "On the Authorities of the Soviet Union in the Transitional Period", replacing itself with the Supreme Soviet of the Soviet Union.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Two new legislative chambers – the Soviet of the Union (Совет Союза) and the Soviet of Republics (Совет Республик) – replaced the Soviet of the Union and the Soviet of Nationalities (both elected by the USSR Congress of People's Deputies).
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The Soviet of the Union was to be formed by the popularly elected USSR people's deputies and would only consider issues concerning civil rights and freedoms and other issues which did not fall under the jurisdiction of the Soviet of Republics.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Its decisions would have to be reviewed by the Soviet of Republics.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The Soviet of Republics was to include 20 deputies from each union republic and one deputy to represent each autonomous region of each union republic (both Soviet people's deputies and republics' people's deputies) delegated by the legislatures of the union republic.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Russia, with 52 delegates, was an exception.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] However, the delegation of each union republic was to have only one vote in the Soviet of Republics.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The laws were to be first adopted by the Soviet of the Union and then by the Soviet of Republics, which would set procedures for the central government, approve the appointment of central ministers and consider inter-republic agreements.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Also created was the Soviet State Council (Государственный совет СССР), which included the Soviet president and the presidents of union republics.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The "Committee for the Operational Management of the Soviet Economy" was replaced by the USSR Inter-republic Economic Committee (Межреспубликанский экономический комитет СССР), also headed by Ivan Silayev.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] On 6 September, the newly created Soviet State Council recognized the independence of Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] On 9 September, the Supreme Soviet of Tajikistan declared the independence of Tajikistan from the Soviet Union.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Also in September, over 99% percent of voters in Armenia voted for independence of the republic in a referendum.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The immediate aftermath of the vote was the Armenian Supreme Soviet's declaration of independence on 21 September.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] On 27 October, the Supreme Soviet of Turkmenistan declared the independence of Turkmenistan from the Soviet Union.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] On 1 December, Ukraine held a referendum, in which more than 90% of residents supported the Act of Independence of Ukraine.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] By November, the only Soviet Republics that had not declared independence were Russia, Kazakhstan and Uzbekistan.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] That same month, seven republics (Russia, Belarus, Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, Kyrgyzstan, Turkmenistan, and Tajikistan) agreed to a new union treaty that would form a confederation called the Union of Sovereign States.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] However, this confederation never materialized.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] On 8 December, Boris Yeltsin, Leonid Kravchuk and Stanislav Shushkevich – the leaders of Russia, Ukraine, and Belarus (which had adopted the name in August 1991) – as well as the prime ministers of the three republics, met in Minsk, Belarus, to sign the Belovezha Accords.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The accords declared that the Soviet Union had ceased to exist "as a subject of international law and geopolitical reality".
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] It repudiated the 1922 union treaty that established the Soviet Union and established the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) in the Union's place.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] On 12 December, the Supreme Soviet of the Russian SFSR ratified the accords and recalled the Russian deputies from the Supreme Soviet of the USSR.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Although this has been interpreted as the moment that Russia seceded from the union, Russia took the position that it was not possible to secede from a state that no longer existed.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The lower chamber of the Supreme Soviet, the Council of the Union, was forced to halt its operations, as the departure of the Russian deputies left it without a quorum.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Doubts remained about the legitimacy of the 8 December accords, since only three republics took part.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Thus, on 21 December in Alma-Ata, the Alma-Ata Protocol expanded the CIS to include Armenia, Azerbaijan, Moldova and the five republics of Central Asia.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] They also preemptively accepted Gorbachev's resignation.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] No member state of the UN formally objected to this step.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The legitimacy of this act has been questioned by some legal scholars as the Soviet Union itself was not constitutionally succeeded by the Russian Federation, but merely dissolved.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Others argued that the international community had already established the precedent of recognizing the Soviet Union as the legal successor of the Russian Empire, and so recognizing the Russian Federation as the Soviet Union's successor state was valid.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] On 25 December, Gorbachev announced his resignation as President of the Soviet Union.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The red hammer and sickle flag of the Soviet Union was lowered from the Senate building in the Kremlin and replaced with the tricolour flag of Russia.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] All former Soviet embassies became Russian embassies, and Russia received all nuclear weapons located in other former republics by 1996.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] A constitutional crisis in late 1993 escalated into violence, and the new Russian constitution that came into force at the end of the year abolished the last vestiges of the Soviet political system.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] On 1 November 1991, the RSFSR Congress of People's Deputies issued Decision No.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] 1831-1 "On the Legal Support of the Economic Reform" whereby the Russian president (Boris Yeltsin) was granted the right to issue decrees required for economic reform even if they contravened existing laws.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Such decrees entered into force if they were not repealed within 7 days by the Supreme Soviet of the Russian SFSR or its Presidium.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Five days later, Boris Yeltsin, in addition to his duties as president, assumed those of the prime minister.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Yegor Gaidar became deputy prime minister and simultaneously economic and finance minister.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] On 15 November 1991, Boris Yeltsin issued Decree No.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] 213 "On the Liberalization of Foreign Economic Activity on the Territory of the RSFSR", whereby all Russian companies were allowed to import and export goods and acquire foreign currency (all foreign trade had previously been tightly controlled by the state).
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] 213, on 3 December 1991 Boris Yeltsin issued Decree No.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] 297 "On the Measures to Liberalize Prices", whereby from 2 January 1992, most previously existing price controls were abolished.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The GKChP members and their accomplices were charged with treason in the form of a conspiracy aimed at capturing power.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] However, by January 1993, they had all been released from custody pending trial.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The trial in the Military Chamber of the Russian Supreme Court began on 14 April 1993.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] On 23 February 1994, the State Duma declared amnesty for all GKChP members and their accomplices, along with the participants of the October 1993 crisis.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] They all accepted the amnesty, except for General Varennikov, who demanded the continuation of the trial and who was finally acquitted on 11 August 1994.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] The Russian Procuracy also wanted to charge former Deputy Defense Minister Vladislav Achalov, but the Russian Supreme Soviet refused to lift his immunity.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Additionally, the Procuracy refrained from charging numerous other individuals accused of complicity in the coup, including the Army Chief of Staff.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Thousands of people attended the funeral of Dmitry Komar, Ilya Krichevsky, and Vladimir Usov on 24 August 1991.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Gorbachev posthumously made the three Heroes of the Soviet Union for their bravery in "blocking the way to those who wanted to strangle democracy.".
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] In 1991, a parliamentary commission tasked with investigating causes for the attempted coup was established under Lev Ponomaryov, but was dissolved in 1992 at Ruslan Khasbulatov's insistence.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] On 24 August 1991, Sergey Akhromeyev was found dead in his office, serving as the Advisor to the president of USSR.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] On 26 August, Nikolay Kruchina was found dead near his residence in the morning, having jumped from the window of his apartment a few hours prior.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] He served as the Managing Director of the Central Committee of the CPSU.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] His predecessor, Georgiy Pavlov, followed the same fate on 6 October of the same year.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] On 17 October, former Deputy Head of the International Department of the Central Committee of the CPSU Dmitriy Lisovolik was found dead, having also jumped from the window of his apartment.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p01] Said deaths have faced extensive scrutiny by historians and contemporaries, who noted the similarities with which these people died.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p02] Many but not all of states still officially Marxist–Leninist (not former Warsaw Pact members that had begun transitioning to a multi-party system) had supported the coup, while others left ambivalent or unofficial support and reversed their position when the coup failed.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p02] The Warsaw Pact had dissolved in July, and its members had rapidly changed, with Marxist–Leninist pro-Soviet governments deposed or elected out of office.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p02] As a result, all criticized or expressed weary sentiments about events in Moscow.
[src:crimean-war/1991-soviet-coup-attempt-p02] Some former Warsaw Pact members deployed armed forces to strategically important areas.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] In September and October 1993, a constitutional crisis arose in the Russian Federation from a conflict between the then Russian president Boris Yeltsin and the country's parliament.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Yeltsin performed a self-coup, dissolving parliament and instituting a presidential rule by decree system.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The crisis ended with Yeltsin using military force to attack Moscow's House of Soviets and arrest the lawmakers.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] In Russia, the events are known as the "**October Coup**" (Russian: Октябрьский путч, romanized: *Oktyabr'skiy putch*) or "**Black October**" (Чëрный октябрь, *Chornyi Oktyabr'*).
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] With the dissolution of the Soviet Union in December 1991, the Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic turned into an independent country, the Russian Federation.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The Soviet-era 1978 Russian constitution remained in effect, though it had been amended in April 1991 to install a president independent of the parliament.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Boris Yeltsin, elected president in July 1991, began assuming increasing powers, leading to a political standoff with Russia's parliament, which in 1993 was composed of the Congress of People's Deputies and the Supreme Soviet.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] On 23 September, the parliament (led by Supreme Soviet Chairman Ruslan Khasbulatov) impeached Yeltsin, proclaimed vice president Alexander Rutskoy the acting president, and barricaded itself in the White House building.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Ten days of street fighting commenced between police and demonstrators loyal to Yeltsin and the parliamentarians.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] On 3 October, demonstrators removed militia cordons around the parliament and, urged by their leaders, took over the mayor's offices and tried to storm the Ostankino television centre.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] On 4 October, the army, which had remained neutral, shelled the White House using tanks and stormed the building with special forces on Yeltsin's orders, arresting the surviving leaders of the resistance.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] All of those involved in the events were later granted amnesty by the State Duma in February 1994 and released from jail.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] At the climax of the crisis, Russia was thought by some to be "on the brink" of civil war.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The ten-day conflict became the deadliest single event of street fighting in Moscow's history since the October Revolution; 147 people were killed and 437 wounded according to the official Russian government statistics.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] In the wake of the events, Yeltsin consolidated his position, further expanded the powers of the executive, and pushed through the adoption of the 1993 constitution of the Russian Federation.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The Soviet Union was dissolved on 26 December 1991 and the Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic gained its independence as the Russian Federation.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] In Russia, Yeltsin's economic reform program took effect on 2 January 1992.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Soon afterward, prices skyrocketed, government spending was slashed, and heavy new taxes went into effect.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] A deep credit crunch shut down many industries and led to a protracted depression.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] As a result, unemployment reached record levels.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The program began to lose support, and the ensuing political confrontation between Yeltsin on one side, and the opposition to radical economic reform on the other, became increasingly centered in the two branches of government.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Throughout 1992, opposition to Yeltsin's reform policies grew stronger and more intractable among bureaucrats concerned about the condition of Russian industry and among regional leaders who wanted more independence from Moscow.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Russia's vice president, Alexander Rutskoy, denounced the Yeltsin program as "economic genocide".
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] From 1991 to 1998, the first seven years of Yeltsin's incumbency, the Russian GDP (measured by purchasing power parity) went from over two trillion U.S. dollars annually to less than one and a quarter trillion U.S. per annum.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The United States provided an estimated $2.58 billion of official aid to Russia during the eight years of Bill Clinton's presidency, to build a new economic system, and he encouraged American businesses to invest.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Leaders of oil-rich republics such as Tatarstan and Bashkiria called for full independence from Russia.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Also throughout 1992, Yeltsin wrestled with the Supreme Soviet (the standing legislature) and the Russian Congress of People's Deputies (the country's highest legislative body, from which the Supreme Soviet members were drawn) for control over government and government policy.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] In 1992 the speaker of the Russian Supreme Soviet, Ruslan Khasbulatov, came out in opposition to the reforms, despite claiming to support Yeltsin's overall goals.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Yeltsin, awaiting implementation of his privatization program, demanded that parliament reinstate his decree powers (only parliament had the authority to replace or amend the constitution).
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] In the Russian Congress of People's Deputies and in the Supreme Soviet, the deputies refused to adopt a new constitution that would enshrine the scope of presidential powers demanded by Yeltsin into law.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Another cause of conflict also called repeated refusal of the Congress of People's Deputies to ratify the Belovezha Accords on the termination of the existence of the USSR, and to exclude from the text of the Constitution of the RSFSR of 1978 references to the Constitution and laws of the USSR.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] During its December session, the parliament clashed with Yeltsin on a number of issues, and the conflict came to a head on 9 December when the parliament refused to confirm Yegor Gaidar, the widely unpopular architect of Russia's "shock therapy" market liberalizations, as prime minister.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The parliament refused to nominate Gaidar, demanding modifications of the economic program and directed the Central Bank, which was under the parliament's control, to continue issuing credits to enterprises to keep them from shutting down.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] In an angry speech the next day on 10 December, Yeltsin accused the Congress of blocking the government's reforms and suggested the people decide on a referendum, "which course do the citizens of Russia support?
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The course of the President, a course of transformations, or the course of the Congress, the Supreme Soviet and its Chairman, a course towards folding up reforms, and ultimately towards the deepening of the crisis." Parliament responded by voting to take control of the army.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Yeltsin nominated Viktor Chernomyrdin to be prime minister on 14 December, and the parliament confirmed him.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Yeltsin's December 1992 compromise with the seventh Congress of the People's Deputies temporarily backfired.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Early 1993 saw increasing tension between Yeltsin and the parliament over the language of the referendum and power sharing.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] In a series of collisions over policy, the congress whittled away the president's extraordinary powers, which it had granted him in late 1991.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The legislature, marshaled by Khasbulatov, began to sense that it could block and even defeat the president.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The tactic that it adopted was gradually to erode presidential control over the government.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] In response, the president called a referendum on a constitution for 11 April.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The eighth Congress of People's Deputies opened on 10 March 1993, with a strong attack on the president by Khasbulatov, who accused Yeltsin of acting unconstitutionally.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] In mid-March, an emergency session of the Congress of People's Deputies voted to amend the constitution, strip Yeltsin of many of his powers, and cancel the scheduled April referendum, again opening the door to legislation that would shift the balance of power away from the president.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The president stalked out of the congress.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Vladimir Shumeyko, first deputy prime minister, declared that the referendum would go ahead, but on 25 April.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The parliament was gradually expanding its influence over the government.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] On 16 March, the president signed a decree that conferred Cabinet rank on Viktor Gerashchenko, chairman of the central bank, and three other officials; this was in accordance with the decision of the eighth congress that these officials should be members of the government.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The congress' ruling, however, had made it clear that as ministers they would continue to be subordinate to parliament.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] In general, the parliament's lawmaking activity decreased in 1993, as its agenda increasingly became dominated by efforts to increase the parliamentarian powers and reduce those of the president.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Yeltsin also bitterly attacked the parliament, accusing the deputies of trying to restore the Soviet-era order.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] On 23 March, although not yet possessing the signed document, the Constitutional Court ruled that some of the measures proposed in Yeltsin's TV address were unconstitutional; however, the decree itself, that was only published a few days later, did not contain unconstitutional steps.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The ninth congress, which opened on 26 March, began with an extraordinary session of the Congress of People's Deputies taking up discussions of emergency measures to defend the constitution, including impeachment of President Yeltsin.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Yeltsin conceded that he had made mistakes and reached out to swing voters in parliament.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Yeltsin narrowly survived an impeachment vote on March 28, votes for impeachment falling 72 short of the 689 votes needed for a 2/3 majority.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] These groups, together with more centrist groups like Change (Смена), left the opposing bloc of Yeltsin supporters (Democratic Russia and Radical Democrats) in a clear minority.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The referendum would go ahead, but since the impeachment vote failed, the Congress of People's Deputies sought to set new terms for a popular referendum.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The legislature's version of the referendum asked whether citizens had confidence in Yeltsin, approved of his reforms, and supported early presidential and legislative elections.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The parliament voted that in order to win, the president would need to obtain 50 percent of the whole electorate, rather than 50 percent of those actually voting, to avoid an early presidential election.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] This time, the Constitutional Court supported Yeltsin and ruled that the president required only a simple majority on two issues: confidence in him, and economic and social policy; he would need the support of half the electorate in order to call new parliamentary and presidential elections.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] On 25 April, a majority of voters expressed confidence in the president, and called for new legislative elections.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Yeltsin termed the results a mandate for him to continue in power.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Before the referendum, Yeltsin had promised to resign, if the electorate failed to express confidence in his policies.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Although this permitted the president to declare that the population supported him, not the parliament, Yeltsin lacked a constitutional mechanism to implement his victory.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] As before, the president had to appeal to the people over the heads of the legislature.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] On 1 May, antigovernment protests organized by the hardline opposition turned violent.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Numerous deputies of the Supreme Soviet took part in organizing the protest and in its course.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] One OMON police officer suffered fatal injuries during the riot.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] As a reaction, a number of the representatives of Saint Petersburg intelligentia (e.g., Oleg Basilashvili, Aleksei German, Boris Strugatsky) sent a petition to president Yeltsin, urging "putting an end to the street criminality under political slogans".
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] On 29 April 1993, Boris Yeltsin released the text of his proposed constitution to a meeting of government ministers and leaders of the republics and regions, according to ITAR-TASS.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] After much hesitation, the Constitutional Committee of the Congress of People's Deputies decided to participate and present its own draft constitution.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Of course, the two main drafts contained contrary views of legislative–executive relations.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Some 700 representatives at the conference ultimately adopted a draft constitution on 12 July that envisaged a bicameral legislature and the dissolution of the congress.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] But because the convention's draft of the constitution would dissolve the congress, there was little likelihood that the congress would vote itself out of existence.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The Supreme Soviet immediately rejected the draft and declared that the Congress of People's Deputies was the supreme lawmaking body and hence would decide on the new constitution.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The parliament was active in July–August, while the president was on vacation, and passed a number of decrees that revised economic policy, in order to "end the division of society", It also launched investigations of key advisers of the president, accusing them of corruption.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The president returned in August and declared that he would deploy all means, including circumventing the constitution, to achieve new parliamentary elections.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] In July, the Constitutional Court of the Russian Federation confirmed the election of Pyotr Sumin to head the administration of the Chelyabinsk Oblast, something that Yeltsin had refused to accept.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] As a result, a situation of dual power existed in that region from July to October in 1993, with two administrations claiming legitimacy simultaneously.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Another conflict involved the decision of the Constitutional Court regarding the regional presidency in Mordovia.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The court delegated the question of legality of abolishing the post of the region's president to the Constitutional Court of Mordovia.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] As a result, popularly elected President Vasily Guslyannikov, member of the pro-Yeltsin Democratic Russia movement, lost his position.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Thereafter, the state news agency (ITAR-TASS) ceased to report on a number of Constitutional Court decisions.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The Supreme Soviet also tried to further foreign policies that differed from Yeltsin's line.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Thus, on 9 July 1993, it passed resolutions on Sevastopol, "confirming the Russian federal status" of the city.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Ukraine saw its territorial integrity at stake and filed a complaint to the Security Council of the UN.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Yeltsin condemned the resolution of the Supreme Soviet.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] In August 1993, a commentator reflected on the situation as follows: "The President issues decrees as if there were no Supreme Soviet, and the Supreme Soviet suspends decrees as if there were no President." (*Izvestiya*, August 13, 1993).
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The president launched his offensive on 1 September when he attempted to suspend Vice President Rutskoy, a key adversary.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Rutskoy, elected on the same ticket as Yeltsin in 1991, was the president's automatic successor.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] A presidential spokesman said that he had been suspended because of "accusations of corruption", due to alleged corruption charges, which was not further confirmed.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] On 3 September, the Supreme Soviet rejected Yeltsin's suspension of Rutskoy and referred the question to the Constitutional Court.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Two weeks later, Yeltsin declared that he would agree to call early presidential elections provided that the parliament also called elections.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] On 18 September, Yeltsin then named Yegor Gaidar, who had been forced out of office by parliamentary opposition in 1992, a deputy prime minister and a deputy premier for economic affairs.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] This appointment was unacceptable to the Supreme Soviet.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] At the same time, Yeltsin repeated his announcement of a constitutional referendum, and new legislative elections for December.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] He also repudiated the Constitution of 1978, declaring that it had been replaced with one that gave him extraordinary executive powers.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] According to the new plan, the lower house would have 450 deputies and be called the State Duma, the name of the Russian legislature before the Bolshevik Revolution in 1917.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The Federation Council, which would bring together representatives from the 89 subdivisions of the Russian Federation, would assume the role of an upper house.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Yeltsin claimed that by dissolving the Russian parliament in September 1993 he was clearing the tracks for a rapid transition to a functioning market economy.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] With this pledge, he received strong backing from the leading powers of the West.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Yeltsin enjoyed a strong relationship with the Western powers, particularly the United States, but the relationship made him unpopular with many Russians.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] In Russia, the Yeltsin side had control over television, where hardly any pro-parliament views were expressed during the September–October crisis.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Rutskoy called Yeltsin's move a step toward a *coup d'état*.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The next day, the Constitutional Court held that Yeltsin had violated the constitution and could be impeached.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] During an all-night session, chaired by Khasbulatov, parliament declared the president's decree null and void.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Rutskoy was proclaimed acting president until new elections.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] He dismissed the key ministers Pavel Grachev (defense), Nikolay Golushko (security), and Viktor Yerin (interior).
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Russia now had two presidents and two ministers of defense, security, and interior.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Although Gennady Zyuganov and other top leaders of the Communist Party of the Russian Federation did not participate in the events, individual members of communist organizations actively supported the parliament.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] On 23 September, with the observance of a quorum, the Congress of People's Deputies was convened (the quorum was 638).
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The same day, Yeltsin announced presidential elections for June 1994.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] On 24 September, the Congress of People's Deputies voted to hold simultaneous parliamentary and presidential elections by March 1994.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Yeltsin scoffed at the parliament-backed proposal for simultaneous elections, and responded the next day by cutting off electricity, phone service, and hot water in the parliament building.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Yeltsin also sparked popular unrest with his dissolution of a Congress and parliament increasingly opposed to his neoliberal economic reforms.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Tens of thousands of Russians marched in the streets of Moscow seeking to bolster the parliamentary cause.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The demonstrators were protesting against the deteriorating living conditions.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Since 1989, the GDP had been declining, corruption was rampant, violent crime was skyrocketing, medical services were collapsing and life expectancy falling.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Yeltsin was also increasingly getting the blame.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] It is still hotly debated among Western economists, social scientists, and policy-makers as to whether or not the IMF, World Bank, and U.S.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Treasury Department-backed reform policies adopted in Russia, often called "shock therapy", were responsible for Russia's poor record of economic performance in the 1990s or rather that Yeltsin had not gone far enough.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Under the Western-backed economic program adopted by Yeltsin, the Russian government took several radical measures at once that were supposed to stabilize the economy by bringing state spending and revenues into balance and by letting market demand determine the prices and supply of goods.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Under the reforms, the government let most prices float, raised taxes, and cut back sharply on spending in industry and construction.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] These policies caused widespread hardship as many state enterprises found themselves without orders or financing.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The rationale of the program was to squeeze the built-in inflationary pressure out of the economy so that the newly privatized producers would begin making sensible decisions about production, pricing and investment instead of chronically overusing resources, as in the Soviet era.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] By letting the market rather than central planners determine prices, product mixes, output levels, and the like, the reformers intended to create an incentive structure in the economy where efficiency and risk would be rewarded and waste and carelessness were punished.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Removing the causes of chronic inflation, the reform's architects argued, was a precondition for all other reforms.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Hyperinflation would wreck both democracy and economic progress, they argued; only by stabilizing the state budget could the government proceed to restructure the economy.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] A similar reform program had been adopted in Poland in January 1990, with generally favorable results.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Outside Moscow, the Russian masses overall were confused and disorganized.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Nonetheless, some of them also tried to voice their protest, and sporadic strikes took place across Russia.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The protesters included supporters of various communist (Labour Russia) and nationalist organizations, including those belonging to the National Salvation Front.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] A number of armed militants of Russian National Unity took part in the defense of the Russian White House, as reportedly did veterans of Tiraspol and Riga OMON.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The presence of Transnistrian forces, including the KGB detachment 'Dnestr', stirred General Alexander Lebed to protest against Transnistrian interference in Russia's internal affairs.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] On 28 September, Moscow saw the first bloody clashes between the special police and anti-Yeltsin demonstrators.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Also on the same day, the Russian Interior Ministry moved to seal off the parliament building.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Barricades and wire were put around the building.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] On 1 October, the Interior Ministry estimated that 600 fighting men with a large cache of arms had joined Yeltsin's political opponents in the parliament building.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The Congress of People's Deputies still did not discount the prospect of a compromise with Yeltsin.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The Russian Orthodox Church acted as a host to desultory discussions between representatives of the Congress and the president.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The negotiations with the Russian Orthodox Patriarch Alexy II as mediator continued until 2 October.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] On the afternoon of 3 October, the Moscow Municipal Militsiya failed to control a demonstration near the White House, and the political impasse developed into armed conflict.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] On 2 October, supporters of parliament constructed barricades and blocked traffic on Moscow's main streets.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Rutskoy signed a decree that had no practical consequences on the release of Viktor Chernomyrdin from the post of prime minister.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] On the afternoon of 3 October, armed opponents of Yeltsin successfully stormed the police cordon around the White House territory, where the Russian parliament was barricaded.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Paramilitaries from factions supporting the parliament, as well as a few units of the internal military (armed forces normally reporting to the Ministry of Interior), supported the Supreme Soviet.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Rutskoy greeted the crowds from the White House balcony, and urged them to form battalions and to go on to seize the mayor's office and the national television center at Ostankino.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Khasbulatov also called for the storming of the Kremlin and imprisoning "the criminal and usurper Yeltsin" in Matrosskaya Tishina.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] At 16:00 Yeltsin signed a decree declaring a state of emergency in Moscow.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] On the evening of 3 October, after taking the mayor's office located in the former Comecon HQ nearby, pro-parliament demonstrators and gunmen led by General Albert Makashov moved toward Ostankino, the television center.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] But the pro-parliament crowds were met by Militsiya and OMON forces who took positions in and around the TV complex.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Part of the TV center was significantly damaged.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Television stations went off the air and 46 people were killed, according to official Russian state estimates, including Terry Michael Duncan, an American lawyer, who was in Moscow to establish a law firm and was killed while attempting to help the wounded.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The government originally refused to report the number killed, which led to reports that as many as 1,500 people were killed.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Before midnight, the Interior Ministry's units had turned back the parliament loyalists.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] When broadcasting resumed late in the evening, vice-premier Yegor Gaidar called on television for a meeting in support of democracy and President Yeltsin "so that the country would not be turned yet again into a huge concentration camp".
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] A number of people with different political convictions and interpretations over the causes of the crisis (such as Grigory Yavlinsky, Alexander Yakovlev, Yury Luzhkov, Ales Adamovich, and Bulat Okudzhava) also appealed to support the President.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Similarly, the Civic Union bloc of 'constructive opposition' issued a statement accusing the Supreme Soviet of having crossed the border separating political struggle from criminality.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Several hundred of Yeltsin's supporters spent the night in the square in front of the Moscow City Hall preparing for further clashes, only to learn in the morning of 4 October that the army was on their side.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The Ostankino killings went unreported by Russian state television.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The only independent Moscow radio station's studios were burnt.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Two French, one British, and one American journalist were killed by sniper fire during the massacre.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] A fifth journalist died from a heart attack.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The press and broadcast news were censored starting on 4 October, and by the middle of October, prior censorship was replaced by punitive measures.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Between 2 and 4 October, the position of the army was the deciding factor.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The military equivocated for several hours about how to respond to Yeltsin's call for action.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] By this time dozens of people had been killed and hundreds had been wounded.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Rutskoy, as a former general, appealed to some of his ex-colleagues.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] After all, many officers and especially rank-and-file soldiers had little sympathy for Yeltsin.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The supporters of the parliament did not send any emissaries to the barracks to recruit lower-ranking officer corps, making the fatal mistake of attempting to deliberate only among high-ranking military officials who already had close ties to parliamentary leaders.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] In the end, a prevailing bulk of the generals did not want to take their chances with a Rutskoy–Khasbulatov regime.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Some generals had stated their intention to back the parliament, but at the last moment moved over to Yeltsin's side.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The plan of action was proposed by Captain Gennady Zakharov.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Ten tanks were to fire at the upper floors of the White House, with the aim of minimizing casualties but creating confusion and panic amongst the defenders.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Five tanks were deployed at Novy Arbat bridge and the other five at Pavlik Morozov playground, behind the building.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Then, special troops of the Vympel and Alpha units would storm the parliament premises.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] According to Yeltsin's bodyguard Alexander Korzhakov, firing on the upper floors was also necessary to scare off snipers.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] By sunrise on 4 October, the Russian army encircled the parliament building, and a few hours later army tanks began to shell the White House, punching holes in the front of it.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] At 8:00 am Moscow time, Yeltsin's declaration was announced by his press service.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Yeltsin assured the listeners: "The fascist-communist armed rebellion in Moscow shall be suppressed within the shortest period.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The Russian state has necessary forces for this." By noon, troops entered the White House and began to occupy it, floor by floor.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Rutskoy's desperate appeal to Air Force pilots to bomb the Kremlin was broadcast by the Echo of Moscow radio station but went unanswered.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] He also tried to have the Chairman of the Constitutional Court, Valery Zorkin, call the Western embassies to guarantee Rutskoy's and his associates' safety – to no avail.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Hostilities were stopped several times to allow some in the White House to leave.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] By mid-afternoon, popular resistance in the streets was completely suppressed, barring occasional sniper fire.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The "second October Revolution", as it came to be known, saw the deadliest street fighting in Moscow since 1917.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Some claim Yeltsin was backed by the military only grudgingly, and only "at the eleventh hour".
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The instruments of coercion gained the most, and they would expect Yeltsin to reward them in the future.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] A paradigmatic example of this was General Pavel Grachev, who had demonstrated his loyalty during this crisis.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Grachev became a key political figure, despite many years of charges that he was linked to corruption within the Russian military.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The Russian public opinion research institute VCIOM, a state-controlled agency, conducted a poll in the aftermath of October 1993 events and found out that 70% of the people polled thought that the use of military force by Yeltsin was justified and 30% thought it was not justified.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] This support for Yeltsin's actions declined in later years.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] When VCIOM-A asked the same question in 2010, only 41% agreed with the use of the military, with 59% opposed.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] When asked about the main cause of the events of 3–4 October, 46% in the 1993 VCIOM poll blamed Rutskoy and Khasbulatov.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Nine years following the crisis, the most popular culprit was the legacy of Mikhail Gorbachev with 36%, closely followed by Yeltsin's policies with 32%.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] In the aftermath of the collapse of the Soviet Union, miner unions tended to support Yeltsin due to an informal alliance that had emerged between the two, where Yeltsin promised to meet their economic demands.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] On 5 October 1993, the newspaper *Izvestia* published the open letter "Writers demand decisive actions of the government" to the government and President signed by 42 well-known Russian literati and hence called the Letter of Forty-Two.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] In the weeks following the storming of the White House, Yeltsin issued a barrage of presidential decrees intended to consolidate his position.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] On 5 October, Yeltsin banned political leftist and nationalist organizations and newspapers like *Den'*, *Sovetskaya Rossiya* and *Pravda* that had supported the parliament (they would later resume publishing).
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] In an address to the nation on 6 October, Yeltsin also called on those regional Soviets that had opposed him – by far the majority – to disband.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Valery Zorkin, chairman of the Constitutional Court, was forced to resign.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The chairman of the Federation of Independent Trade Unions was also sacked.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The anti-Yeltsin TV broadcast *600 Seconds* of Alexander Nevzorov was ultimately closed down.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Yeltsin decreed on 12 October that both houses of parliament would be elected in December.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] On 15 October, he ordered that a popular referendum be held in December on a new constitution.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Rutskoy and Khasbulatov were charged on 15 October with "organizing mass disorders" and imprisoned.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] On 23 February 1994, the State Duma amnestied all individuals involved in the events of September–October 1993.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] They were later released in 1994 when Yeltsin's position was sufficiently secure.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] In early 1995, the criminal proceedings were discontinued and were eventually placed into the archives.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] "Russia needs order," Yeltsin told the Russian people in a television broadcast in November in introducing his new draft of the constitution, which was to be put to a referendum on 12 December.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The new basic law would concentrate sweeping powers in the hands of the president.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The bicameral legislature, to sit for only two years, was restricted in crucial areas.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The president could choose the prime minister even if the parliament objected and could appoint the military leadership without parliamentary approval.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] He would head and appoint the members of a new, more powerful security council.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] If a vote of no confidence in the government was passed, the president would be enabled to keep it in office for three months and could dissolve the parliament if it repeated the vote.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The president could veto any bill passed by a simple majority in the lower house, after which a two-thirds majority would be required for the legislation to be passed.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The president could not be impeached for contravening the constitution.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] The central bank would become independent, but the president would need the approval of the State Duma to appoint the bank's governor, who would thereafter be independent of the parliament.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] At the time, most political observers regarded the draft constitution as shaped by and for Yeltsin and perhaps unlikely to survive him.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] On 12 December, Yeltsin managed to push through his new constitution, creating a strong presidency and giving the president sweeping powers to issue decrees; however, the parliament elected on the same day (with a turnout of about 53%) delivered a stunning rebuke to his neoliberal economic program.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Unexpectedly, the most surprising insurgent group proved to be the ultranationalist Liberal Democratic Party led by Vladimir Zhirinovsky.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] It gained 23% of the vote while the Gaidar-led Russia's Choice received 15.5% and the Communist Party of the Russian Federation, 12.4%.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Zhirinovsky alarmed many observers abroad with his neo-fascist and chauvinist declarations.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Nevertheless, the referendum marked the end of the constitutional period defined by the constitution adopted by the Russian SFSR in 1978, which was amended many times while Russia was a part of Mikhail Gorbachev's Soviet Union.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Although Russia would emerge as a dual presidential–parliamentary system in theory, substantial power would rest in the president's hands.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Russia now had a prime minister who heads a cabinet and directs the administration.
[src:crimean-war/1993-russian-constitutional-crisis] Despite officially following a semi-presidential constitutional model, the system was effectively an example of president–parliamentary presidentialism because the prime minister is appointed and in effect freely dismissed by the president.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] A dispute over Tuzla Island in the Kerch Strait arose between Russia and Ukraine in 2003, sparked by unannounced Russian construction of a causeway from their side of the strait toward the island, which is Ukrainian territory.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] Russians offered various reasons for building the causeway, but Ukraine saw it as a threat to their territorial integrity.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] The dispute raised fears of an armed confrontation, but a settlement was negotiated.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] Tuzla Island is a sandy island off the coast of the Crimean Peninsula.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] Formerly a spit connected by land to the Kuban region of Russia, it was disconnected from it by a heavy storm in 1925.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] In 1941, the island was transferred to the Crimean Autonomous Socialist Soviet Republic, which was part of the Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] It became the Crimean Oblast in 1945, and the oblast was transferred to the Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic in 1954.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] Tuzla Island came under the control of the briefly independent Republic of Crimea before joining with Ukraine when the Crimean parliament joined Ukraine in 1995.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] Russia recognized Ukrainian sovereignty over Crimea in the Russian–Ukrainian Friendship Treaty of 1997, but the status of Tuzla Island was not settled and remained a sore spot in Russia–Ukraine relations.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] The governor of Krasnodar Krai, Alexksandr Tkachyov, said in 2003, "...
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] I think that this is land that was bathed in Cossack blood, and therefore it is our sacred land," claiming the island as part of Russia.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] Tkachyov later met with the deputy speaker of the Russian duma, Vladimir Zhirinovsky, who then claimed that the majority of the Duma backed the Russian claim over Tuzla Island.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] Controlling the island would give either country much control over the shipping to the Sea of Azov and for that reason it was seen as a priority for the Ukrainian government.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] In 2003, the island was home to a dozen families of Ukrainian fishermen, and two vacation resorts.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] On September 9, 2003, Russians began construction of a causeway from the Taman Peninsula in Krasnodar Krai towards Tuzla Island.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] The work began rapidly, without notice, with up to 180 dump truck loads of earth an hour being dropped into the sea.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] There were several stories regarding what entity in Russia authorised the construction.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] One had it that a local self-government body of the Kuban Cossacks authorised construction to reduce saltwater flow to Taman Bay, to thus improve conditions for certain species of fish.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] According to this story, many Kuban Cossack activists were among the construction workers.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] Kyiv newspaper *Zerkalo Nedeli* suggested that it was supported by local Crimean and Russian businessmen and Ukrainian Communist politician Leonid Hrach to convince Ukraine and Russia to build a bridge over Kerch Strait to facilitate trade.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] Officials in Krasnodar Krai said they were just rebuilding the pre-1925 land connection, to protect their coastal area from flooding.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] The central government in Moscow likewise said it was to prevent erosion of the coast.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] Romanian-American political analyst Vladimir Socor claimed that the construction was by Russia's Ministry of Emergency Situations.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] He said that Russian president Vladimir Putin personally ordered and oversaw the construction, with the purpose of connecting Russia to Tuzla Island, making it part of the Russian mainland.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] He said that Russia was attempting to seize control of the strait's main shipping channel from Ukraine.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] The Ukrainian government responded by deploying border troops of the Simferopol Detachment on the island.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] On October 21, 2003, the Russian tugboat *Truzhenik* crossed the border to photograph and film border posts and defences on the island and was detained by the Border Service of Ukraine.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] The Ukrainians released the tugboat after armed Russian coastal guard boats arrived.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] On October 23, 2003, the Verkhovna Rada issued a resolution "to eliminate a threat to the territorial integrity of Ukraine that appeared as a result of dam construction by the Russian Federation in the strait of Kerch".
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] A provisional special parliamentary commission was created to investigate the case more thoroughly.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] On October 30–31, 2003, talks started between Ukraine and Russia in order to deflate the crisis.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] President Kuchma ended the confrontation through an undeclared compromise, accepting terms disadvantageous to Ukraine, in return for Russian authorities halting construction of the causeway and accepting the continuation of Ukrainian sovereignty over the strait's navigable channel.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] The incident damaged Leonid Kuchma's reputation domestically, as he was accused of attempting to control Ukrainian media reporting on the event.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] Disputes about right of passage were resolved by a 2003 bilateral agreement on cooperation in the use of the Sea of Azov and the Kerch Strait, which made these water bodies shared internal waters of both countries.
[src:crimean-war/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] The island came under full Russian control following the 2014 Russian annexation of Crimea, and they built the Kerch Strait Bridge partly on it.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] The **Crimean War** was fought between Russia and an alliance of the Ottoman Empire, France, the United Kingdom, and Sardinia from October 1853 to February 1856.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] Geopolitical causes of the war included the *Eastern question* (the decline of the Ottoman Empire), the expansion of Russia in the preceding Russo-Turkish wars, and the British and French preference to preserve the Ottoman Empire to maintain the balance of power in the Concert of Europe.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] The war's proximate cause was Tsar Nicholas I's demand that the Ottoman Empire's Orthodox subjects be placed under his protection.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] After the Sublime Porte's refusal, Russian troops occupied the Danubian Principalities in July 1853.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] The Ottomans declared war on Russia in October.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] Fearing the growth of Russian influence and compelled by public outrage over the annihilation of the Ottoman squadron at Sinop, Britain and France joined the war on the Ottoman side in March 1854.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] The Russian advance was halted at Silistria in June.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] In September 1854, after extended preparations, allied forces landed in Crimea in an attempt to capture Russia's main naval base in the Black Sea, Sevastopol.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] They scored an early victory at the Battle of the Alma.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] The Russians counterattacked in late October in what became the Battle of Balaclava and were repulsed, and a second counterattack at Inkerman ended in a Russian defeat.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] The front settled into the 11-month Siege of Sevastopol, involving brutal conditions for troops on both sides.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] Smaller military actions took place in the Caucasus (1853–1855), the White Sea (July–August 1854) and the North Pacific (1854–1855).
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] The Kingdom of Sardinia-Piedmont entered on the allies' side in 1855.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] Sevastopol ultimately fell after a renewed French assault on the Malakoff redoubt in September 1855.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] Diplomatically isolated and facing the prospect of invasion from the west if the war continued, Russia sued for peace in March 1856.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] France and Britain welcomed the development due to the conflict's domestic unpopularity.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] The Treaty of Paris, signed on 30 March 1856, ended the war.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] It forbade Russia to base warships in the Black Sea.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] The Ottoman vassal states of Wallachia and Moldavia became largely independent.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] Christians in the Ottoman Empire gained a degree of official equality, and the Orthodox Church regained control of the Christian churches in dispute.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] The Crimean War was one of the first conflicts in which military forces used modern technologies such as explosive naval shells, railways, and telegraphs.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] It was also one of the first to be documented extensively in written reports and in photographs.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] The war quickly symbolized logistical, medical and tactical failures and mismanagement.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] The reaction in Britain led to a demand for the professionalization of medicine, most famously achieved by Florence Nightingale, who gained worldwide attention for pioneering modern nursing while she treated the wounded.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] The Crimean War also marked a turning point for the Russian Empire.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] It weakened the Imperial Russian Army, drained the treasury, and undermined its influence in Europe.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] The defeat forced Russia's educated elites to identify the country's fundamental problems.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] It became a catalyst for reforms of Russia's social institutions, including the emancipation reform of 1861, which abolished serfdom in Russia, and overhauls in the justice system, local self-government, education, and military service.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] As the Ottoman Empire steadily weakened during the 19th century, the Russian Empire stood poised to take advantage by expanding southward.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] In the 1850s, the British and the French Empires were allied with the Ottoman Empire and were determined to prevent that from happening.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] In the early 1800s, the Ottoman Empire suffered a number of existential challenges.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] The Serbian Revolution in 1804 resulted in the autonomy of the first Balkan Christian nation under the empire.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] The Greek War of Independence, which began in early 1821, provided further evidence of the empire's internal and military weakness, and the commission of atrocities by Ottoman military forces (see Chios massacre) further undermined the empire.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] The disbandment of the centuries-old Janissary corps by Sultan Mahmud II on 15 June 1826 (Auspicious Incident) helped the empire in the longer term but deprived it of its existing standing army in the short term.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] In 1827, the Anglo-Franco-Russian fleet destroyed almost all of the Ottoman naval forces at the Battle of Navarino.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] In 1830, Greece became independent after ten years of war and the Russo-Turkish War (1828–29).
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] The Treaty of Adrianople (1829) granted Russian and Western European commercial ships free passage through the Black Sea straits.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] Also, the Danubian Principalities (Moldavia and Wallachia) became territories under Russian protection.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] France took the opportunity to occupy Algeria, which had been under Ottoman rule, in 1830.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] In 1831, Muhammad Ali of Egypt, the most powerful vassal of the Ottoman Empire, declared independence.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] Ottoman forces were defeated in a number of battles, which forced Mahmud II to seek Russian military aid.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] A Russian army of 10,000 landed on the shores of the Bosphorus in 1833 and helped prevent the Egyptians from capturing Constantinople.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] "The reasons for the Tsar's disquietude are not obscure.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] Not Turkey alone was threatened by the advance of Ibrahim.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] The rights secured to Russia by a succession of treaties were also directly jeopardized.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] The substitution of a virile Albanian dynasty at Constantinople in place of the effete Osmanlis was the last thing desired by the Power which wished, naturally enough, to command the gate into the Mediterranean".
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] Russia was satisfied with the weak government in Constantinople (Istanbul).
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] As a result, the Treaty of Hünkâr İskelesi was signed and greatly benefited Russia.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] It provided for a military alliance between the Russian and the Ottoman Empires if one of them was attacked, and a secret additional clause allowed the Ottomans to opt out of sending troops but to close the Straits to foreign warships if Russia were under threat.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] Egypt remained nominally under Ottoman sovereignty but was *de facto* independent.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] In 1838 in a situation similar to that of 1831, Muhammad Ali of Egypt was not happy about his lack of control and power in Syria, and he resumed military action.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] Moreover, Muhammad Ali had to admit a formal dependence on the Ottoman sultan.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] After Muhammad Ali refused to obey the requirements of the convention, the allied Anglo-Austrian fleet blockaded the Nile Delta, bombarded Beirut and captured Acre.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] Muhammad Ali then accepted the convention's conditions.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] On 13 July 1841, after the expiry of the Treaty of Hünkâr İskelesi, the London Straits Convention was signed under pressure from the European countries.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] The new treaty deprived Russia of its right to block warships from passing into the Black Sea in case of war.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] Thus, the way to the Black Sea was open for British and French warships during a possible Russo-Ottoman conflict.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] Russian historians tend to view that history as evidence that Russia lacked aggressive plans.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] Vinogradov writes: "The signing of the documents was the result of deliberate decisions: instead of bilateral (none of the great powers recognized this Treaty of Unkiar Skelessi), the new Treaty of London was obligatory for all, it closed the Bosphorus and Dardanelles.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] In the absence of expansion plans, this was a sound decision".
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] In 1838, Britain lost interest in crushing the Ottoman Empire.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] On the contrary, after the conclusion of the trade treaty of 1838 (see Treaty of Balta Liman), Britain received unlimited access to the markets of the Ottoman Empire.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] "Britain imposed on the Porte a Tariff Convention which in effect transformed the Ottoman Empire into a virtual free-trade zone.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] Therefore its trade interests pushed it to protect the integrity of the Ottoman Empire.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] Publicly, European politicians made broad promises to the Ottomans.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] Lord Palmerston, the British Foreign Secretary, said in 1839: "All that we hear about the decay of the Turkish Empire, and its being a dead body or a sapless trunk, and so forth, is pure and unadulterated nonsense.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] Given 10 years of peace under European protection, coupled with internal reform, there seemed to him no reason why it should not become again a respectable Power".
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] Orlando Figes has claimed that "The motives of the British in promoting liberal reforms were not just to secure the independence of the Ottoman Empire against Russia.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] They were also to promote the influence of Britain in Turkey", also: "to promote British free-trade interests (which may have sounded splendid but was arguably damaging to the Ottoman Empire)".
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] "From this moment (1838) the export of British manufactured goods to Turkey rose steeply.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] There was an elevenfold increase by 1850".
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] Assistance from Western European powers or Russia had twice saved the Ottoman Empire from destruction, but the Ottomans also lost their independence in foreign policy.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] Britain and France desired more than any other states to preserve the integrity of the Ottoman Empire because they did not want to see Russia gaining access to the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] Russia, as a member of the Holy Alliance, had operated as the "police of Europe" to maintain the balance of power that had been established in the Congress of Vienna in 1815.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] Russia had assisted Austria's efforts in suppressing the Hungarian Revolution of 1848, and expected a free hand in settling its problems with the Ottoman Empire, the "sick man of Europe".
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] However, Britain could not tolerate Russian dominance of Ottoman affairs, which would challenge its domination of the eastern Mediterranean.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] The goal was to promote year-round trade and a year-round navy.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] Pursuit of that goal brought the emerging Russian state into conflict with the Zaporozhian Cossacks along the lower reaches of the Dnieper River and then the Tatars of the Crimean Khanate and Circassians.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] "The plan to develop Russia as a southern power had begun in earnest in 1776, when Catherine placed Potemkin in charge of New Russia (Novorossiya), the sparsely populated territories newly conquered from the Ottomans on the Black Sea's northern coastline, and ordered him to colonize the area".
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] When Russia conquered those groups and gained possession of their territories, the Ottoman Empire lost its buffer zone against Russian expansion, and both empires came into direct conflict.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] The conflict with the Ottoman Empire also presented a religious issue of importance, as Russia saw itself as the protector of history of the Eastern Orthodox Church under the Ottoman Orthodox Christians, who were legally treated as second-class citizens.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] The Ottoman Reform Edict of 1856, promulgated after the war, largely reversed much of the second-class status, most notably the tax that only non-Muslims paid.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] Britain's immediate fear was Russia's expansion at the expense of the Ottoman Empire.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] The British desired to preserve Ottoman integrity and were concerned that Russia might make advances toward British India or move toward Scandinavia or Western Europe.
[src:crimean-war/crimean-war-p01] A distraction (in the form of the Ottoman Empire) on the Russian southwest flank would mitigate that threat.
